<!--please do not remove fixBunching template-->{{fixBunching|end}}
The '''inauguration of Barack Obama''' as the [[List of Presidents of the United States|44th]] [[President of the United States]] took place on Tuesday, January&nbsp;20, 2009. The [[United States presidential inauguration|inauguration]], which set a record attendance for any event held in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington,&nbsp;D.C.]], marked the commencement of the four-year term of [[Barack Obama]] as President and [[Joe Biden|Joseph Biden]] as [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]. Based on the combined attendance numbers, television viewership and Internet traffic, it was among the most observed events ever by the global audience. 

"A&nbsp;New Birth of Freedom", a phrase from the [[Gettysburg Address]], served as the inaugural theme to commemorate the 200th&nbsp;anniversary of the birth year of [[Abraham Lincoln]]. In his speeches to the crowds, Obama referred to ideals expressed by Lincoln about renewal, continuity and national unity. Obama mentioned these ideals in his speech to stress the need for shared sacrifice and a new sense of responsibility to answer America's challenges at home and abroad. 

Obama and others paid homage to Lincoln in the form of tributes and references during several of the events, starting with a commemorative train tour from {{city-state|Philadelphia|Pennsylvania}} to Washington,&nbsp;D.C. on January&nbsp;17, 2009. The inaugural events held in Washington,&nbsp;D.C. from January&nbsp;18 to January&nbsp;21, 2009 included concerts, a national day of community service on [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Day|Martin&nbsp;Luther King,&nbsp;Jr. Day]], the swearing-in ceremony, luncheon and parade, inaugural balls, and the interfaith [[Inaugural ceremony prayers (US presidential)|inaugural prayer]] service. The [[Oath of office of the President of the United States|presidential oath]] as administered to Obama during his swearing-in ceremony on January&nbsp;20 strayed from the oath of office prescribed in the [[United States Constitution]], which led to its re<U+2011>administration the next evening. 

In addition to a larger than usual celebrity attendance, the [[Presidential Inaugural Committee]] increased its outreach to ordinary citizens to encourage greater participation in inaugural events compared with participation in recent past inaugurations. For the first time, the committee opened the entire length of the [[National Mall]] as the public viewing area for the swearing-in ceremony, breaking with the tradition of past inaugurations. Selected American citizens participated in the train tour and other inaugural events, and a philanthropist organized a People's Inaugural Ball for disadvantaged people who otherwise would be unable to afford to attend the inaugural festivities. Among the celebrations for the inauguration, the committee hosted a first-ever Neighborhood Inaugural Ball with free or affordable tickets for ordinary citizens.
{{TOClimit}}

==Context==
[[File:20081102 Obama-Springsteen Rally in Cleveland.JPG|thumb|Obama campaigning as a symbol of change in {{USCity|Cleveland|Ohio}}]]
The January 20 inauguration marked the formal culmination of the [[Presidential transition of Barack Obama]] that began when he won the United States [[United States presidential election, 2008|presidential election]] on [[Election Day (United States)|November 4, 2008]], and became the [[President-elect of the United States|President-Elect]].<ref name='NYT-Nagourney-2008-11-04'> {{cite news | first= Adam | last= Nagourney | authorlink=Adam Nagourney |coauthors= | title= Obama Wins Election | date= 4 November 2008 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/05/us/politics/05elect.html | work=U.S. Politics | publisher =[[New York Times]] | pages = | accessdate = November 5, 2008}}</ref>  In accordance with [[Article_One_of_the_United_States_Constitution#Section_6:_Compensation.2C_privileges.2C_and_restrictions_on_holding_civil_office|Article I, Section 6]] of the [[United States Constitution]], Obama resigned from the [[United States Senate]] effective November 16, 2008.<ref>Letter of resignation from Barack Obama to [[Richard Cheney]], Nov. 18, 2008; published in the ''[[Congressional Record]]'', Nov. 19, 2008, page S10609 ([http://frwebgate1.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/PDFgate.cgi?WAISdocID=557516393307+3+2+0&WAISaction=retrieve Communication from the Honorable Barack Obama])</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Obama sets date to leave Senate|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/us_elections_2008/7728466.stm|date=November 13, 2008|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2008-11-14}}
</ref> He was formally elected by the [[Electoral College (United States)|Electoral College]] on December 15, 2008.<ref name='Politico-EC'> {{cite news | first= Andy | last= Barr | authorlink= |coauthors= | title= Electoral College weighs in for Obama | date= 15 December 2008 | url = http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1208/16610.html| work=U.S. Politics | publisher =[[Politico]] | pages = | accessdate = December 15, 2008}}</ref>  The results were certified by a joint session of [[United States Congress|Congress]] on January 8, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/news_summaries/2009/01/summary_08.html|title=News Summary for January 8, 2009|accessdate=2010-02-18|date=2009-01-08|publisher=[[Public Broadcasting Service]]|work=[[PBS NewsHour]]}}</ref>
<!--Section is being added to address the following concern: An integral element missing to this article is why this was such a notable event, why it attracted the audience it did, which was a combination of the first black president the US has ever had, and the great sigh of relief that Bush was finally leaving. The raucous celebrations that took place throughout the world upon the Obama's elections were credited to both of these causes. I think the article should start with a brief overview of the campaigns and the results of the election, including a description of the running in the streets and honking of cars etc., that occurred in many locations on election night, plus the incredible problems Obama took on from the previous administration. This ties in with the new day themes of his speeches on the train rides and why he would address crisis issues in the inauguration speech. I think it's notable that Bush was the first president since Jimmy Carter, who surprised the Secret Service by walking from the Capitol to the White House, by not walking since his limo was pelted by eggs from parade attendees. As the first black president, there were some serious concerns about Obama's safety if he decided to get out and walk, which he did. Let me know if you have questions.
        I understand that, but the lead and the entire event surrounds the throng of people, the high price of tickets, the large global audience...for a presidential inauguration? As if Obama's just another president? Well he is, but he's also the first black president and the result of a massive political shove to the previous 8-year administration. I think these issues, with the political tone of his speeches in light of the 2 wars and the near-depression he inherited are integral to the article. An immense amount of pressure was placed on Obama to fix everything, to be the panacea for Americans and this came out ceremonially in his inauguration. Can you update this sentence: ''No one from the crowds at the swearing-in ceremony and parade was arrested as of 6:00 p.m. EST on Inauguration Day''-->

Obama, who originally campaigned using the slogan "Change We Can Believe In" and later "Change We Need",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalradar/2008/09/obamas-change-s.html|title=Obama's 'Change' Slogan Gets a Change|accessdate=2010-02-18|date=2008-09-13|publisher=[[ABC News]] Internet Ventures}}</ref> was widely-celebrated as the first [[African American]] president of the United States and a symbol of change from his [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] predecessor, [[George W. Bush]]. Obama also represented a generational change as the first man elected President who was born in the 1960s. He inherited what [[Peter Orzag]] termed an "economic mess" that became known as the [[financial crisis of 2007<U+2013>2010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/2009/03/08/Orszag-Obama-inherited-economic-woes/UPI-85971236559252/|title=Orszag: Obama inherited economic woes|accessdate=2010-02-18|date=2009-03-08|publisher=[[United Press International]]}}</ref>  According to a [[CNN]] poll, he embodied youthful energy and transition at a time of economic despair, and inspired more confidence than his immediate predecessors.<ref name=kdn/>

==Planning ==
[[File:ObamaInaugurationCapitolPreparation.jpg|thumb|left|250px|alt=U.S. Capitol at dusk, mostly darkened but with dome floodlit from within|Preparations at the [[United States Capitol]]]]
The inauguration was planned primarily by two committees: the [[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]] and the 2009&nbsp;Presidential Inaugural Committee. Although the election was scheduled for November 4, 2008, the congressional committee began construction of the inaugural platform on September 24, 2008.<ref>{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title= Construction of 2009 Inaugural Platform Begins with the Ceremonial Driving of the "First Nail" | date= 2008-09-24 | publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]] | url = http://inaugural.senate.gov/media/releases/release-09242008-inauguralwebsite.cfm | work = Press Release | pages = | accessdate = 2009-06-25}}</ref>

===Joint Congressional Committee===
The swearing-in ceremony and the inaugural luncheon for [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] Obama and Vice President-elect Biden were planned by the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies, a committee composed of [[United States Senator]]s [[Dianne Feinstein]], committee chair, [[Bob Bennett (politician)|Bob Bennett]] and [[Harry Reid]], and [[United States Representative]]s [[John Boehner]], [[Steny Hoyer]] and [[Nancy Pelosi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inaugural.senate.gov/cmte/membershiphistory.cfm|title=Membership of the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|accessdate=2010-02-11|publisher=[[United States Senate]]}}</ref> The committee is overseen by the [[U.S. Senate Committee on Rules and Administration|U.S.&nbsp;Senate Committee on Rules and Administration]]. 

The Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies chose the inaugural theme, "A&nbsp;New Birth of Freedom",<ref name="JCCIC-Inaugural Theme-2008-11-05">{{cite news | first= | last= | coauthors= | title= Senator Feinstein Announces 2009 Inaugural Theme | date= 2008-11-05 | publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]] | url = http://inaugural.senate.gov/media/releases/release-11052008-inauguralwebsite.cfm | work = Press Release | pages = | accessdate = 2009-01-15}}
</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/01132009/news/politics/o_to_arrive_in_a_lincoln_149979.htm|title=O to arrive in a 'Lincoln': Inaugural themes will harken back to great emancipator|last=Lisi|first=Clemente|date=2009-01-13|work=[[The New York Post]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> a phrase from Abraham Lincoln's [[Gettysburg Address]] from the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] era.<ref name="JCCIC-Inaugural Theme-2008-11-05"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Boritt, Gabor|year=2006|title=The Gettysburg Gospel: The Lincoln Speech That Nobody Knows|publisher=Simon&nbsp;& Schuster|page=432|isbn=0743288203}}</ref> The theme, which was selected by the committee to mark the inaugural occasion and honor the 200th&nbsp;anniversary year of Lincoln's birth, expressed "Lincoln's hope that the sacrifice of those who died to preserve the United States would lead to 'a new birth of freedom' for the nation.'"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://inaugural.senate.gov/history/chronology/bhobama2009/theme.cfm|title='A New Birth of Freedom'<U+2014>2009 Inaugural Theme|date=2008|publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]]|accessdate=2009-05-01}}</ref> In his reliance on the inaugural theme, Obama wanted "to give Americans reassurance that today, as in Lincoln's time, the country would find its way through any crisis".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usnews.com/articles/news/obama/2009/01/20/barack-obamas-inauguration-is-one-for-the-history-books.html|title=Barack Obama's Inauguration Is One for the History Books|last=Walsh|first=Kenneth, T.|date=2009-01-20|work=[[U.S. News & World Report|U.S.&nbsp;News&nbsp;& World Report]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref>

The congressional committee released the full schedule of the January&nbsp;20 inaugural events on December&nbsp;17, 2008. The inauguration schedule referred to the President<U+2011>elect as "Barack&nbsp;H. Obama", although Obama specified previously that he intended to use his full name for his swearing-in ceremony, including his middle name [[Husayn|Hussein]].<ref name=ItRNBfUD>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,467607,00.html|title=Obama to Resurrect Middle Name for Inauguration Day|accessdate=2008-12-21|date=2008-12-16|publisher=[[Fox News]]|author=}}</ref> Obama decided to use his full name "Barack Hussein Obama" to "follow the tradition, not trying to make a statement one way or the other" for the inaugural ceremony.<ref name=IBHODSS>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/sleuth/2008/12/president-elect_obama_has_said.html|title=I Barack Hussein Obama Do Solemnly Swear...|accessdate=2009-02-09|date=2008-12-18|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|author=Akers, Mary Beth}}</ref> During the [[United States presidential election, 2008|election]] campaign, Obama's detractors tried to use his middle name to imply falsely that he was a Muslim.<ref name=IBHODSS/>

The [[Council of the District of Columbia|District of Columbia City Council]] passed legislation to enable bars and restaurants to stay open around<U+2011>the<U+2011>clock to provide hospitality services to the inaugural festivities attendees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98280231|title=Inauguration: Expect Nonstop Drink, Crowds|last=Keyes|first=Allison|date=2008-12-21|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|accessdate=2009-05-10}}</ref> After reaching an agreement with the congressional committee, District of Columbia Mayor&nbsp;[[Adrian Fenty]] signed legislation to temporarily allow bars and restaurants to operate 24&nbsp;hours during the weekend leading up to the inauguration, but with 4:00&nbsp;a.m. EST as the cut<U+2011>off for alcoholic beverage service.<ref name=SCEBHfIaBI>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/politics/war_room/2008/12/17/dc_bars/|title=D.C. bars won't stay open quite so late for inauguration|accessdate=2009-02-16|date=2008-12-17|work=[[Salon.com|Salon]]}}
</ref><ref name="JCCIC-alcohol">{{cite web  | last = | title = Senators Feinstein and Bennett Urge DC Government To Reverse Emergency Alcohol Law  | publisher = [[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]] | date = 2008-12-09  | url = http://inaugural.senate.gov/media/releases/release-12102008-fentygray.cfm  | accessdate = 2009-01-24 }}</ref> The Hotel Association of Metropolitan Washington agreed to pay for extended train service provided by the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] on January&nbsp;19 to  accommodate visitors attending inaugural events and workers providing support for those events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/2009/01/metro_extends_service_on_inaug.html|title=Metro Extends Service on Inaugural Eve Until 2 a.m.|accessdate=2009-04-28|date=2009-01-13|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|author=Nakamura, David A}}</ref>

===Presidential Inaugural Committee===
The 2009&nbsp;Presidential Inaugural Committee organized several other inauguration<U+2011>related events at the direction of the President<U+2011>elect and Vice President<U+2011>elect of the United States, such as the train ride, concerts, parade, balls and prayer service.  The co-chairs of the committee were [[William M. Daley|William Daley]], [[Penny Pritzker]], [[John W. Rogers, Jr.|John Rogers]], [[Pat Ryan (executive)|Patrick Ryan]] and [[Julianna Smoot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2008/11/obama_presidential_inauguratio.html|title=Obama Presidential Inauguration Committee announced. Daley, Pritzker, Rogers, Smoot and Ryan co-chair.|accessdate=2009-12-10|date=2008-11-25|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Sweet, Lynn}}</ref>

For the first time in history, the Presidential Inaugural Committee opened the full length of [[National Mall]], which extends from the [[United States Capitol]] to the [[Lincoln Memorial]], as the public viewing area for the swearing-in ceremony.<ref name=foxmall>{{cite news|url=http://origin.foxnews.com/wires/2008Dec04/0,4670,InaugurationMall,00.html|title=National Mall will be open for Obama inauguration|last=Zongker|first=Brett|date=2008-12-04|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref> The presidential committee set aside a section of the mall close to the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol for people holding reserved tickets for the inaugural event.<ref name=foxmall/><ref name=AVGttPIoBO>
{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/articles/news/obama/2008/12/17/a-visitors-guide-to-the-presidential-inauguration-of-barack-obama.html|title=A Visitor's Guide to the Presidential Inauguration of Barack Obama|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-12-17|work=[[U.S. News & World Report|U.S.&nbsp;News&nbsp;& World Report]]|author=Ruggeri, Amanda}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/20/AR2009012004497.html|title=A historic inauguration draws throngs to the Mall.|author=Shear, Michael D. and Kornblut, Anne E.|date=2009-01-21|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|accessdate=2009-01-22.}}</ref> The committee directed the opening of the entire National Mall to make the event "'the most open and accessible in history,' allowing those who [could not] get the [reserved] tickets to the swearing-in ceremony on the Capitol grounds to fill the mall".<ref name=foxmall/> To enable people in attendance to see and hear the swearing-in ceremony, the committee arranged for placement of [[JumboTron]]s at points along the entire mall.<ref name=mall>{{cite news|url=http://washingtonindependent.com/20933/national-mall-will-open-to-public-for-inauguration|title=National Mall Will Open to Public for Inauguration|last=DeLong|first=Matthew|date=2008-12-04|work=The Washington Independent|accessdate=2009-05-06}}</ref>

Despite criticism that such a large event could not be [[Carbon footprint|carbon-friendly]], the presidential committee incorporated [[Zero waste|environment-friendly]] measures in its planning of the inaugural events. The environmental measures included the use of recyclable carpet for the platform, retrieval of recyclable items from outdoor areas after an event,<ref name="green">{{cite web  | last = Yager | first = Jordy | title = Green carpet won<U+2019>t quite cover Inaugural footprint | work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | date = 2008-01-13  | url = http://thehill.com/leading-the-news/green-carpet-wont-quite-cover-inaugural-footprint-2009-01-13.html | accessdate = 2009-04-21 }}</ref> and the use of recycled paper for invitations and inaugural ball tickets.<ref name="green2">{{cite web  | last = Miller | first = Sunlen | title = Obama Team Aims to Go Green This Inaugural | publisher = [[ABC News]] | date = 2008-01-14  | url = http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2009/01/obama-team-aims.html | accessdate = 2009-04-21 }}</ref>

==== Fundraising====
