The 2009 Presidential Inaugural Committee attempted to raise more individual contributions in smaller dollar amounts compared with the [[second inauguration of George W. Bush|second inauguration of George&nbsp;W. Bush]] in 2005. The 2009 contribution limit was set at $50,000&nbsp;for donations by individuals, whereas individuals and companies were able to give a maximum of $250,000 apiece for the 2005 event.<ref name=OistbtmeiUh/> As of January&nbsp;30, 2009, the presidential committee raised more than $53&nbsp;million, with at least 458&nbsp;people giving the committee-imposed maximum of $50,000,<ref name=fundstotal>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2009/01/30/inaugural_fund_raising_exceeds_53m/|title=Inaugural fund-raising exceeds $53m|accessdate=2009-02-01|date=2009-01-30|work=[[The Boston Globe|The&nbsp;Boston Globe]]|author=Mooney, Brian C.}}</ref> including celebrity donors such as [[George Soros]], [[Halle Berry]], [[Jamie Foxx]] and [[George Lucas]].<ref name=Or$mfi>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/sleuth/2008/12/despite_concerns_about_donor_f.html|title=Hollywood Coughs Up Cash for Obama Inaugural|accessdate=2009-03-02|date=2008-12-15|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|author=Akers, Mary Ann}}</ref> Emphasizing a change from business as usual, the committee set stringent guidelines for campaign contributions, barring donations from corporations, [[political action committee]]s, registered federal [[lobbying|lobbyist]]s, [[labor unions|labor and trade unions]], [[Foreign Agents Registration Act|registered foreign agents]] and non-[[United States nationality law|U.S.&nbsp;citizens]].<ref name=fundstotal/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/26/us/politics/26inaug.html?fta=y|title=Obama Places Stringent Limits on Inaugural Contributions|last=Seelye|first=Katherine Q.|date=2008-11-25|publisher=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]] |accessdate=2009-05-10}}</ref> The committee did accept donations from people with active lobbying interests before the federal government, but not registered as federal lobbyists, such as [[Google]] executive [[Eric Schmidt]] and [[Microsoft]] executive [[Steve Ballmer]].<ref name=Or$mfi/>

Based on its fundraising efforts and crowd estimates for the Obama inauguration, the presidential committee set its budget at $160<U+2013>$170&nbsp;million for the inauguration, including about $45&nbsp;million for the gala events.<ref name=fundstotal/> The [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] contributed about $49&nbsp;million, including $1.2&nbsp;million to cover the actual swearing-in ceremony.<ref name=OistbtmeiUh>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/jan/14/barack-obama-inauguration-cost |title=Obama's inauguration set to be the most expensive in US history: The $150m (<U+00A3>102m) cost of the celebration will dwarf the amount spent on George Bush's inauguration in 2005 |accessdate=2009-01-16| date=2009-01-14| work=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[United Kingdom]]| author=MacAskill, Ewen}}</ref><ref name=fundstotal/><ref name="abc">{{cite news |first=Scott |last=Mayerowitz |title=What Recession? The $170&nbsp;million Inauguration |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Business/Inauguration/story?id=6665946&page=1 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=2009-01-19 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref> The District of Columbia and the neighboring states of [[Maryland]] and [[Virginia]] projected costs to provide support for inaugural events at more than $75&nbsp;million alone for police, fire and medical services.<ref name=OistbtmeiUh/><ref name="abc"/> To help fund the efforts, President [[George W. Bush]] declared a federal [[state of emergency]] as a precaution so that funds could be sought from [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/13/bush-declares-state-of-emergency-for-inauguration/|title=Bush Declares State of Emergency for Inauguration|accessdate=2009-04-28|date=2009-01-13|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Stolberg, Sheryl Gay}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2009/01/13/inauguration-watch-a-state-of-emergency/|title=Inauguration Watch: A State of Emergency?|accessdate=2009-04-28|date=2009-01-13|work=[[Wall Street Journal]]|author=McKinnon, John D.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/2009/01/bush_declares_state_of_emergen.html|title=Bush Declares State of Emergency for Inauguration|accessdate=2009-04-28|date=2009-01-13|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|author=Nakamura, David A.}}</ref>

===Invitations and tickets===
{{main|Invitations to the inauguration of Barack Obama}}
The Presidential Inaugural Committee and members of the [[111th United States Congress|111th U.S.&nbsp;Congress]] distributed invitations and color-coded tickets to both [[Very Important Person|dignitaries]] and ordinary citizens for the reserved sections on or near the [[United States Capitol|U.S.&nbsp;Capitol]] grounds to view the swearing-in ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mgwashington.com/index.php/news/article/obamas-inauguration-will-be-tough-ticket/2119/|title=Obama<U+2019>s inauguration will be tough ticket|last=Dominello|first=Amy|date=2008-11-10|publisher=Media General News Service|accessdate=2009-04-23}}</ref> [[Invitations to the inauguration of Barack Obama|Invitations]] and tickets were sent to ambassadors and chiefs of diplomatic missions to the United States and their spouses, but not to other representatives of foreign countries, and invitations were distributed to U.S.&nbsp;politicians and an array of dignitaries across the spectrum of business and industry. [[United States House of Representatives|House]] and [[United States Senate|Senate]] congressional members distributed free tickets for the inaugural ceremony to the public by lottery or on a first<U+2011>come, first served basis because of overwhelming requests to attend the event.<ref>
{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/Congress-to-Distribute-Inaugural-Tickets-Starting-Monday.html|title=Congress to receive inaugural tickets today|date=2009-01-13|publisher=[[WRC-TV]] (Washington, D.C.)|accessdate=2009-01-21}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/01/12/tickets-obama-inauguration-create-stir-capitol-hill|title=Tickets to Obama inauguration create stir on Capitol Hill|author=Pergram, C.|date=2009-01-12|publisher=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|accessdate=2009-01-21}}</ref>

Because of high demand and limited availability of the reserved tickets, some people planned to offer their tickets for sale through ticket brokers, Internet auctions and classified listing services.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/reutersComService_2_MOLT/idUSTRE50D7O220090115|title=Senate votes to ban inauguration ticket scalping|date=2009-01-14|publisher=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref> Sales offers for tickets reached as high as $1,750 each for the reserved standing room section behind the [[United States Capitol Complex|Capitol Reflecting Pool]], $5,500 each for the reserved standing room section in front of the Reflecting Pool and $20,000 each for the VIP section on the Capitol grounds.<ref name=tixscalping>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/washingtonpostinvestigations/2009/01/inaugural_tickets_still_sellin.html|title=$20K Inaugural Tickets for Sale as Congress Debates Ban|last=Kravitz|first=Derek|date=2009-01-14|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref> In one case, a former legislative aide to Representative [[Ted Poe]] was exposed by a prospective buyer after the former aide used [[Craigslist]] and e<U+2011>mail to offer five tickets to the buyer for $4,500.<ref name>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/sleuth/2009/01/selling_inauguration_tickets_i.html|title=Senate Cracks Down On Inaugural Scalping After GOP Aide Nabbed |last=Akers|first=Mary Ann|date=2009-01-13|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|accessdate=2009-05-12}}</ref>

Federal and state officials became concerned about [[Ticket resale|ticket scalping]] and fraud related to sales of the tickets for the swearing-in ceremony.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-obamatix14-2008nov14,0,6959444.story|title=EBay removes offers of Obama inauguration tickets|date=2008-11-14|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref> Senator Dianne Feinstein, chair of the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies, introduced legislation in mid-November 2008 to ban sales of tickets to the swearing-in ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lostintransition.nationaljournal.com/2008/11/ban-on-scalping-inaugural-tickets-stalls.php|title=Ban On Scalping Inaugural Tickets Stalls In Senate|last=Harder|first=Amy|date=2008-11-21|work=[[National Journal]]|accessdate=2009-05-05}}</ref> At the same time, the joint congressional committee contacted online auction operators, ticket resellers and classified listing services to block sales of the tickets. To address the committee's concerns, [[StubHub]] and [[eBay]] agreed to ban ticket sales for the swearing-in ceremony on all of its sites.<ref name=tixscalping/><ref name=latimes/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/leading-the-news/feinstein-praises-ebay-for-banning-inauguration-ticket-sales-2008-11-13.html|title=Feinstein lauds eBay for ticket ban |last=Yager |first=Jordy|date=2008-11-13|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref> Senator Feinstein re-introduced legislation in December 2008 to ban ticket sales for the swearing-in ceremony after amending the bill to exempt tickets issued by official presidential inaugural committees for inaugural event fundraising.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lostintransition.nationaljournal.com/mt/mt-search.cgi?tag=Legislation&blog_id=49&IncludeBlogs=49|title=Feinstein Releases Text Of Scalping Bill|last=Harder|first=Amy|date=2009-01-07|work=[[National Journal]]|accessdate=2009-05-05}}</ref> The U.S.&nbsp;Senate failed to pass the final bill, which caused the bill to die in the closing days of the [[lame duck (politics)#United_States|lame duck]] legislative session.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lostintransition.nationaljournal.com/2008/12/inaugural-scalping-ban-dies-in-senate.php|title=Ban On Scalping Inaugural Tickets Dies In Senate|last=Harder|first=Amy|date=2008-12-15|work=[[National Journal]]|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref>

==Pre-inaugural events==
===Train ride: Commemorating Lincoln===
On January 17, 2009, Obama hosted a [[whistle stop train tour]] in honor of the 200th&nbsp;anniversary of the birth year of Abraham Lincoln. Obama reenacted the final part of Lincoln's 1861&nbsp;train tour from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania to Washington,&nbsp;D.C.<ref name="USAToday-Jackson-2008-12-19">
{{cite-news | url= http://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-12-15-obamatrain_N.htm?csp=34| title=Obama's inaugural train to start in Philly|accessdate= 2008-12-19|date= 2008-12-15| work=[[USA Today]]| last =Jackson | first = David}}
</ref><ref name=OAiWATT/> to capture the mood of the 1861&nbsp;[[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]] to Washington train tour traveled by Lincoln to his own [[Abraham Lincoln 1861 presidential inauguration|inauguration]].<ref name=OtrtDiattL>{{cite news|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%20125D724FC484A978%20)&p_docid=125D724FC484A978&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=125D724FC484A978&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=H52P4FFJMTI0MTc4OTMzNS44MTA2Nzk6MToxMDoxMjguMTIuMC4w&&p_multi=DFPB|title=Obama Train Ride To D.C. Is A Tribute To Lincoln|accessdate=2009-04-12|date=2009-01-17|publisher=[[NewsBank]]|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Gray, Kathleen}}</ref><ref name=Ostrrthi>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/17/obama.train/|title=Obama set to ride rails to historic inauguration|accessdate=2009-01-17|date=2009-01-17|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]}}</ref> For his train ride to the nation's capital, Obama rode in the [[Georgia 300|Georgia&nbsp;300]], a vintage railroad car used by past presidents and the same one he used for touring Pennsylvania during his [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2008|presidential primary campaign]].<ref name=prestour>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2009/01/aboard_the_obama_express.html|title=Aboard the Obama express|last=Sweet|first=Lynn|date=2009-01-17|work=[[Chicago Sun Times]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> On the tour, Obama was accompanied by his wife Michelle, their daughters Malia and Sasha, and a host of friends and guests.<ref name=prestour/>

[[File:Obama train ride.jpg|thumb|left|225px|alt=Obama is standing aboard the back platform of a train and looking to the side of the train.  There is a red, white and blue banner hanging over the rear railing.|Obama aboard the [[Georgia 300|Georgia&nbsp;300]] on January&nbsp;17, 2009]]
For the train ride to Washington, Obama invited 41&nbsp;"everyday Americans" that he met during his presidential campaign to accompany him on the tour and attend other inaugural events, including the swearing-in ceremony, the parade and an inaugural ball.<ref name=OtrtDiattL/><ref name=OTTRTH>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/01/17/national/inauguration09/main4729489.shtml?source=related_story|title=Obama Takes Train Ride To History: President-Elect Retraces Lincoln's Route From Philadelphia To Washington; Next Stop: Inauguration|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-17|publisher=[[CBS News]]}}</ref><ref name=citizens/>  The group of citizens who joined the tour had shared stories with then-candidate Obama about themselves and their families during the presidential campaign, and included Matt Kuntz and [[Lilly Ledbetter]].<ref name=citizens/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/story?id=6669384&page=1|title=Obama Express Pulls Into Home Station: 'You're Never Too Old to Toot the Horn,' President-Elect Jokes|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-17|publisher=[[ABC News]]|author=Khan, Huma, Sunlen Miller and Jake Tapper}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/01/17/eveningnews/main4731162.shtml|title=An "Everyday" American On Obama's Train: CBS Evening News: Dover Teacher And Anti-Domestic Violence Advocate Among Passengers On Historic Trip|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-17|publisher=[[CBS News]] |author=David, Priya}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2009-01-15-obamasupporters_N.htm|title=Obama's connections, from campaign trail to inaugural train|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-16|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Keily, Kathy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gadsdentimes.com/article/20090108/NEWS/901070283|title=Ledbetter to ride on Obama's train tour|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-08|work=[[Gadsden Times]]|location=[[Gadsden, Alabama|Gadsden, AL]]}}</ref> Kuntz, who lost his own step<U+2011>brother to [[suicide]] after returning home from the [[Gulf War|Gulf&nbsp;War]], dedicated his efforts to improve mental health screening for [[Iraq War|Iraq&nbsp;War]] veterans.<ref name=citizens>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/national/president/37200584.html?elr=KArksi8D3PE7_8yc+D3aiUo8D3PE7_eyc+D3aiUeyc+D3aUU|title=Obama invites 'Everyday Americans' to join Whistle Stop Tour to DC for inaugural festivities|date=2009-01-07|publisher=''[[Star Tribune]]'' (Minnesota)|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> Ledbetter, who learned years later that her employer had discriminated against her in pay based on gender, lost her case before the Supreme Court because she did not file her claim within 180&nbsp;days of the discriminatory act.<ref name=citizens/> Nine days after his inauguration, Obama as president signed into law the [[Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act of 2009|Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act]], allowing claims filed against employers not only within 180&nbsp;days of the pay discrimination, but also restarting the 180-day period for claims upon receiving any paycheck based on a discriminatory pay action.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/jan/29/obama-signs-ledbetter-fair-pay-act|title=Obama signs Ledbetter fair-pay act|last=Bellantoni|first=Christina|date=2009-01-29|work=[[The Washington Times|The&nbsp;Washington Times]]|accessdate=2009-04-30}}</ref>

Obama commenced the tour in Philadelphia by holding a town hall meeting at [[30th Street Station|30th&nbsp;Street Station]] with a few hundred supporters.<ref name=OAiWATT>{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Zeleny |title= Obama arrives in Washington after train trip |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/18/us/politics/18obama.html?ref=politics |work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|date=2009-01-17 |accessdate=2009-02-08}}</ref><ref name=OtcIlyb>{{cite news |title=Obama to crowds: 'I love you back'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/17/obama.train/|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|date=2009-02-08 |accessdate=2009-01-17}}</ref> At the first stop in [[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington]], [[Delaware]] Vice President<U+2011>elect Biden and his family joined the tour. Biden, dubbed "Amtrak Joe" for his daily commutes on [[Amtrak]] between Wilmington and Washington, built a reputation as a supporter of increased funding for U.S. commuter [[rail transport]]ation.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/09/16/riding-the-rails-with-amtrak-joe/ | title=Riding the Rails With Amtrak Joe | last=Leibovich| first=Mark | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=2008-09-16 | accessdate=2000-05-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/23/fashion/23biden.html|title='Amtrak Joe' No More|last=Bosman|first=Julie|date=2008-11-21|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|accessdate=2009-05-01}}</ref> The train continued to [[Baltimore]], Maryland, its second stop, where Obama spoke to a crowd of about 40,000&nbsp;people.<ref name=OAiWATT/> 

During his speeches to the crowds, he emphasized the theme "A New Birth of Freedom" using phrases associated with Lincoln such as "better angels" and "a new declaration of independence".<ref name=OAiWATT/> Obama referred to [[Patriot (American Revolution)|patriotic]] forebearers in his speech when he reminded the crowds that "we should never forget that we are the heirs of that first band of patriots, ordinary men and women who refused to give up when it all seemed so improbable; and who somehow believed that they had the power to make the world anew."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/wires/ap/2009/01/17/D95P6A8O0_obama_whistle_stop_text/print.html|title=Text of Obama's speech in Philadelphia|date=2009-01-17|work=[[Salon.com|Salon]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> Thousands of well<U+2011>wishers gathered at various points along the train route taking pictures, cheering and waving [[Flag of the United States|American flag]]s and homemade signs,<ref name=OAiWATT/><ref name=OAiWATT/> with Obama reciting his trademark rejoinder "I&nbsp;love&nbsp;you back" to the enthusiastic crowds.<ref name=OtcIlyb/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/22/us/politics/22obama.html|title=After a Year on the Road, Obama Is Changing His Tempo |accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2008-10-21|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Powell, Michael}}</ref> The one-day train tour concluded at [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]] in Washington,&nbsp;D.C.<ref name=OtrtDiattL/>

===We Are One concert===
{{main|We Are One: The Obama Inaugural Celebration at the Lincoln Memorial}}
[[File:20090118 We Are One.jpg|thumb|right|225px|alt=The Obamas wave as they walk past military flagbearers in the background while a couple stands in the foreground.|The Obamas wave at the crowd at the [[We Are One: The Obama Inaugural Celebration at the Lincoln Memorial|We Are One]] concert held at the [[Lincoln Memorial]] on January 18, 2009.]]
On January 18, 2009, the day after Obama arrived in Washington,&nbsp;D.C., an inaugural concert, "We Are One", took place at the [[Lincoln Memorial]]. The concert featured performances and readings of historical passages by more than three dozen celebrities.<ref name=WAOTOIC>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117939371.html?categoryid=1264&cs=1|title=We Are One: The Obama Inaugural Celebration|accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2009-01-18|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Gallo, Phil}}</ref><ref name=JBAFasaOip>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/13/entertainment/et-cause13|title=Jonas Brothers, Aretha Franklin among stars at Obama inauguration parties|accessdate=2009-01-18|date=2009-01-13|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Daunt, Tina}}</ref> Attendance at the concert was free to the public, and [[HBO]] broadcast the concert live on an open feed, enabling anyone with cable television to watch the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/springsteen-bono-beyonce-play-obama-inaugural-concert|title=Springsteen, Bono, Beyonce to Play Obama Inaugural Concert |accessdate=2009-01-18|date=2009-01-12|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|author=Fitzmaurice, Larry}}</ref> An estimated 400,000&nbsp;people attended the concert at the Lincoln Memorial.<ref name=MSSRR/> The [[Washington Metro]] recorded 616,324&nbsp;passenger trips during the day, breaking the old Sunday ridership record of 540,945&nbsp;passenger trips set on July&nbsp;4, 1999.<ref name=MSSRR>{{cite web|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/getthere/2009/01/metro_sets_sunday_ridership_re.html|title=Metro Sets Sunday Ridership Record|accessdate=2009-01-20|date=2009-01-19|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|author=McPhate, Mike}}</ref>

===King Day of Service===
The eve of the Inauguration Day, January 19, 2009, fell on Martin&nbsp;Luther King,&nbsp;Jr.&nbsp; Day, a U.S. federal holiday in recognition of [[Martin Luther King, Jr.|Dr. King]]'s&nbsp;birthday. Obama called upon communities everywhere to observe the King Day of Service, a day of citizen volunteer service honoring the human rights leader.<ref name=OCfNDoS>{{cite news|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/17/obama-calls-for-national-day-of-service/|title=Obama Calls for National Day of Service|accessdate=2009-01-25|date=2008-12-17|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Seelye, Katharine Q.}}</ref><ref name=OCMDwS/> More than 13,000&nbsp;community service events took place across the nation on the day, the largest participation in the 14 years since Congress passed the King Holiday and Service Act and more than double the previous year's events.<ref name=KingDay>{{cite news|url=http://www.mlkday.gov/about/newsroom/releases_detail.asp?tbl_pr_id=1213|title=Yes We Did! 2009 King Day of Service is Largest Ever|accessdate=2009-05-09|date=2009-01-23}}</ref>

Obama spent an hour at [[Walter Reed Army Medical Center]] meeting privately with the families of troops who were recovering from wounds sustained in the [[Iraq War|Iraq&nbsp;War]] and the [[War in Afghanistan (2001<U+2013>present)|War&nbsp;in Afghanistan]].<ref name=OCMDwS>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/19/AR2009011901189.html|title=Obama Commemorates MLK Day with Service|accessdate=2009-01-25|date=2009-01-19|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|author=Branigin, William and Philip Rucker}}</ref><ref name=WvttadosOnhm>{{cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/about/chi-011909-obama-service-jan20,0,3440131.story|title=With visit to troops and day of service, Obama nears his moment|accessdate=2009-04-15|date=2009-01-19|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=''[[Hartford Courant]]''|author=James, Frank}}</ref> After visiting the medical center, he, along with [[Martin Luther King, III|Martin&nbsp;Luther King,&nbsp;III]], headed to the Sasha Bruce House [[homeless shelter]] for teens to participate with others in service activities.<ref name=OCMDwS/><ref name=WvttadosOnhm/>

Joe Biden hung [[drywall]] at a [[Habitat for Humanity]] home in [[Northeast, Washington, D.C.|N.E.&nbsp;Washington,&nbsp;D.C.]]<ref name=OCMDwS/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%20125E8F19514F4E10%20)&p_docid=125E8F19514F4E10&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=125E8F19514F4E10&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=X56I53NNMTI0MTc5MDM2Ny4xODI2NDY6MToxMDoxMjguMTIuMC4w&&p_multi=USTB|title=Obamas, Bidens participate in 'call to service'|accessdate=2009-04-12|date=2009-01-22|publisher=[[NewsBank]]|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Gaudiano, Nicole}}</ref> Biden's wife, [[Jill Biden|Jill]], their daughter, Ashley Biden, [[Michelle Obama]] and the Obamas' daughters, Malia and Sasha, spent the morning at [[Robert F. Kennedy Stadium]] where they helped thousands of volunteers prepare more than 85,000 [[care package]]s destined for U.S.&nbsp;troops overseas.<ref name=KingDay/><ref name=WvttadosOnhm/><ref name=HDKLaSA>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/dr_king_service/|title=Honoring Dr. King<U+2019>s Legacy and Serving America|accessdate=2009-01-26|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[Whitehouse.gov]]}}</ref> Later that evening, the president-elect hosted three separate bipartisan dinners to honor the service of [[John McCain|John&nbsp;McCain]], [[Colin Powell|Colin&nbsp;Powell]] and Joe&nbsp;Biden.<ref name=OCMDwS/><ref name=WvttadosOnhm/>

===Kids' Inaugural: "We Are the Future"===
On the evening of January 19, 2009, Michelle Obama and Jill Biden hosted the "Kids' Inaugural: We Are the Future" event at the [[Verizon Center]]. [[Miley Cyrus]] and the [[Jonas Brothers]] honored military families in concert.<ref name=MOMC/> The show was broadcast live on the [[Disney Channel]] and on [[Radio Disney]].<ref name=JBAFasaOip/> Other celebrity participants included [[Demi Lovato]], [[Bow Wow]], [[George Lopez]], [[Corbin Bleu]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Billy Ray Cyrus]], [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Jamie Foxx]].<ref name=MOMC/> In keeping with the service theme of the day, Michelle Obama issued a call for children to become engaged in public service by volunteering in homeless shelters, visiting elderly people or writing letters to U.S.&nbsp;troops.<ref name=MOMC>{{cite web|url=http://www.wusa9.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=80624&catid=158|title=Michelle Obama, Miley Cyrus: Favorites At Concert |accessdate=2009-02-13|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA-TV (Washington,&nbsp;D.C.)]]|author=Cyr, Emily}}</ref>

==Inaugural events==
{{seealso|United States presidential inauguration}}
===Ceremony: "A New Birth of Freedom"===
[[File:President Obama Swearing In Ceremony.jpg|thumb|225px|alt=View of a large portion of a large ceremony with visible red, white and blue ornamentation and a crowd of attendees|Obama takes the [[Oath of office of the President of the United States|oath of office]] on January&nbsp;20, 2009 at the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol.]]
The inaugural ceremony took place at the West Front of the United States Capitol on January&nbsp;20, 2009. The ceremony opened with the playing of pre<U+2011>recorded music and a live performance by [[United States Marine Band|"The President's&nbsp;Own" United States Marine Band]], followed by live performances by the [[San Francisco Boys Chorus|San&nbsp;Francisco Boys Chorus]] and [[San Francisco Girls Chorus|San&nbsp;Francisco Girls Chorus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inaugural.senate.gov/media/releases/release-011109-ticketinfo.cfm|title=JCCIC Releases Map and Ticket Information for Inaugural Swearing-in Ceremonies|accessdate=2009-03-02|date=2009-01-11|publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]]}}</ref><ref name=IM/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98467663|title=Pre-Inaugural Jitters At San Francisco Chorus|accessdate=2009-03-02|date=2008-12-18|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|author=Mullane, Nancy}}</ref> Senator&nbsp;Dianne Feinstein, chair of the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies and the first woman to preside over a U.S.&nbsp;presidential inauguration, acted as the day's [[Master of Ceremonies]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Feinstein plays key role|url=http://www3.signonsandiego.com/stories/2009/jan/21/1n21notebook002133-feinstein-plays-key-role/?uniontrib|work=[[San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=January 21, 2009|publisher=[[Copley News Service]]|accessdate=2009-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=[[Associated Press]] and [[Agence France-Presse]]|title=Millions witness moment|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/World/Story/STIStory_328905.html|date=January 21, 2009|work=[[The Straits Times]]|location=([[Singapore]])|accessdate=2009-01-20}}</ref><ref name="webcast">{{cite web|url=http://inaugural.senate.gov/history/chronology/bhobama2009.cfm|title=Inauguration of President Barack Obama, 2009|accessdate=2009-04-15|publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]]}}</ref>

[[File:Inauguration performance of Air and Simple Gifts.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Four male musicians playing a variety of instruments outdoors in front of a chain link fence|From left to right: [[Itzhak Perlman]], [[Gabriela Montero]], [[Yo-Yo Ma|Yo-Yo&nbsp;Ma]] and [[Anthony McGill]] performing "[[Air and Simple Gifts]]" at the inauguration. Obama officially became the president at noon during this performance.]]
[[Evangelicalism|Evangelical]] pastor [[Rick Warren]] delivered the [[invocation]] for the inaugural ceremony,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/12/17/obama.warren/index.html|title=Obama's inaugural choice sparks outrage|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-12-18|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|author=Mooney, Alexander}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/20/us/politics/20warren.html?scp=1&sq=pastor%20controversy&st=cse|title=Obama<U+2019>s Choice of Pastor Creates Furor|author=Zeleny, Jeff|coauthor=Kirkpatrick, David D.|accessdate=2009-03-06|date=2008-12-19|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]}}</ref> followed by a performance by vocalist [[Aretha Franklin]], who sang "[[My Country, 'Tis of Thee]]". The program featured a performance of [[John Williams]]' composition "[[Air and Simple Gifts]]",<ref name=IBHODSS/> which was both pre-recorded and performed live synched with the recording by cellist [[Yo-Yo Ma|Yo-Yo&nbsp;Ma]], violinist [[Itzhak Perlman]], pianist [[Gabriela Montero]] and clarinetist [[Anthony McGill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/23/arts/music/23band.html?_r=1&hp|title=The Frigid Fingers Were Live, but the Music Wasn<U+2019>t|date=2009-01-29|accessdate=2009-03-06|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Wakin, Daniel J.}}</ref><ref name=AFtsaOi>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28282312/|title=Aretha Franklin to sing at Obama inauguration: Yo-Yo Ma played cello, accompanied by violinist Itzhak Perlman|accessdate=2008-12-21|date=2008-12-17|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[MSNBC.com]]|author=}}</ref> [[National Public Radio]] described the performance by the quartet as "a&nbsp;transporting moment that moved many with its beauty and calm", while ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it the "classical-music equivalent of lip-syncing".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99816993|title=Yo-Yo Ma On Recorded Music At Inauguration: What's The Big Deal With Inauguration 'Lip-Synching'?|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-23|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|author=Grundmann, Anya}}</ref> Aretha Franklin made a fashion statement by wearing a hat with a distinctive [[Swarovski]] crystal-studded bow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1603107/20090120/franklin_aretha.jhtml|title=Aretha Franklin's Performance At Barack Obama's Inauguration: A Milestone in a Historic Career: Soul singer, who performed 'My Country 'Tis of Thee,' also sang at Martin&nbsp;Luther King's funeral.|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-20|author=Wiederhorn, Jon|publisher=[[MTV Networks]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/alltherage/2009/01/inaugural-hat-t.html|title=All The Rage: The Image Staff Muses On The Culture Of Keeping Up Appearances In Hollywood And Beyond|accessdate=2009-03-05|date=2009-01-20|author=Wiederhorn, Jon|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>

Vice President<U+2011>elect Biden took his oath from [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Associate Justice]] [[John Paul Stevens]].<ref name=AFtsaOi/><ref name=honors>{{cite news|url=http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=weeklyreport-000003013113&cpage=2|title=Step by Step through the day: The symbols of power|accessdate=2010-02-12|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[CQ Politics]]}}</ref> After he completed his oath of office, Biden received in his honor as the new Vice President the first playing of four [[ruffles and flourishes]] and the march "[[Hail, Columbia]]" by members of the armed forces.<ref name=IM>{{cite web|url=http://www.marineband.usmc.mil/whats_new/inauguration_music.htm|title=Inauguration Music|accessdate=2009-03-07|date=2009-03-06|publisher=[[United States Marine Corps]]}}</ref><ref name=vphonors>{{cite news|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/1004393/Q-A-The-US-presidential-inauguration|title=Q&A: The US presidential inauguration|author=Jones, Bryony|accessdate=2010-02-12|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[World News Australia]]}}</ref> After the performance of "Air and Simple Gifts", [[Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[John G. Roberts|John Roberts]] administered the [[Oath of office of the President of the United States|oath of office]] to President<U+2011>elect Obama shortly after noon.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/obama_inauguration/7839229.stm|title=Historic moment as Obama sworn in|accessdate=2010-02-12|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[BBC News]]|location=[[United Kingdom]]}}</ref> The inaugural ceremony ran longer than scheduled, which delayed the administering of the oath so that it finished around 12:05&nbsp;p.m.&nbsp;EST (17:05&nbsp;UTC).<ref name=LIb>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/tv/2009/01/the-burning-question-of-inauguration-morning-was-would-the-superlatives-run-out-before-the-day-does---before-the-sun-came-u.html|title=Live Inauguration blog|accessdate=2009-04-15|date=2009-01-20|work=[[Sun Sentinel]]|location=[[Broward County, Florida|Broward County, FL]]|author=Jicha, Tom}}</ref><ref name=LB>{{cite web|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/live-blog-the-inauguration-of-barack-obama/|title=Live Blog: The Inauguration of Barack Obama|accessdate=2009-04-15|date=2009-01-20|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Seelye, Katharine}}</ref> However, Obama assumed the presidency at the expiration of President&nbsp;Bush's term at noon under the [[Twentieth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]. After he completed the presidential oath, Obama received in his honor as the new President the [[21-gun salute]], and the first playing of four ruffles and flourishes and the march "[[Hail to the Chief]]" by members of the armed forces.<ref name=honors/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/Inaugural%20Media%20Guide.pdf|title=The 56th Presidential Inauguration|accessdate=2010-02-12|date=2009-01|publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]]|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>

Obama delivered his inaugural address to the crowds as the President of the United States following his swearing-in ceremony.<ref name="President Obama">{{cite news | url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28745226/| title=President Obama promises 'hope over fear': First black leader makes history at crucial time for his nation | publisher=[[Msnbc.com|MSNBC.com]] | date=2009-01-20 | accessdate=2009-01-20}}</ref> Poet [[Elizabeth Alexander (poet)|Elizabeth Alexander]] then delivered the inaugural poem, "[[Praise Song for the Day]]",<ref name=AFtsaOi/><ref name=CQpoem>{{cite web|url=http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000003013281|title=CQ Transcript: Elizabeth Alexander<U+2019>s Inaugural Poem|accessdate=2009-01-20|date=2008-01-20|work=[[Congressional Quarterly]]}}</ref> and civil rights activist [[Joseph Lowery]], minister of the [[United Methodist Church]], delivered the [[benediction]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99268371|title=Civil rights icon to deliver inaugural benediction|last=Kohr|first=Kathy|date=2009-01-13|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref> The [[United States Navy Band|United States Navy Band "Sea Chanters"]] chorus concluded the ceremony with a performance of the United States national anthem, [[The Star-Spangled Banner]].<ref name=AFtsaOi/> 

====Oath of office====
<!-- Due to technical limitations, please do not embed the HD version of the video. (WP:CMF) -->
{{Listen
 |header=Presidential Oath of Office
 |filename=Barack Obama Oath of Office.ogg
 |title=Taking the Oath at the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol
 |description=Barack Obama takes the presidential<br>oath administered by Chief Justice John Roberts on January&nbsp;20, 2009.
 |pos=right
 |type=sound
 |header=Presidential Oath of Office
 |help=no
 |filename2=President Obama Re-Takes Oath.ogg
 |title2=Re-taking Oath at the White House
 |description2=Chief Justice Roberts re-administers the presidential oath to President Obama on January&nbsp;21, 2009.
 |pos=right
 |type=sound
 |header2=Retaking the Presidential Oath
 |help=no
}}Chief Justice [[John Roberts]] administered the oath of office of the President of the United States to Obama. Michelle Obama held the [[Lincoln Bible|Bible]], which was used by Abraham Lincoln at his 1861 inauguration, as Barack Obama placed his hand on the Bible and recited the presidential oath.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/12/23/obama-to-take-oath-on-same-bible-as-lincoln/|title=Obama to Take Oath on Same Bible as Lincoln|author=Seelye, Katherine Q.|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|date=2008-12-23|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.usatoday.com/onpolitics/inauguration/page/2/|title=Obama to be sworn in on Lincoln Bible|last=Memmott|first=Mark|date=2008-12-23|work=USA Today|accessdate=2009-05-08}}</ref> 

During the swearing-in ceremony, Obama did not recite, and Roberts as the administering official did not execute, the 35<U+2011>word oath of office exactly as prescribed by the United States Constitution. The first misstep occurred during the first part of the oath. Roberts had not yet completed the first phrase when Obama began reciting the oath. After the correct recitation of the first phrase of the presidential oath, Roberts recited incorrectly the next part of the oath by saying "that I will execute the Office of President ''to'' the United States ''faithfully''", rather than "that I will ''faithfully'' execute the Office of President ''of'' the United States". Obama recited the words "I will execute", and then paused.<ref name=NYTretake/> Roberts then tried to correct his mistake in administering the oath by reciting "faithfully the Office of President of the United States", followed by Obama repeating Roberts' first incorrect phrase.<ref name="oathflub">{{cite news |first=Pete |last=Williams |title=About That oath flub |url=http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/archive/2009/01/20/1751351.aspx |publisher=[[MSNBC.com]] |date=2008-01-20 |accessdate=2009-01-21 }}</ref><ref name=OCJRSiRoPO>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/01/20/chief-justice-roberts-officiates-inauguration/|title=Obama, Chief Justice Roberts Stumble in Recitation of Presidential Oath: Chief Justice John Roberts officiated over his first inauguration Tuesday by swearing in President-elect Barack Obama as president of the United States.|accessdate=2009-02-01|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[Fox News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/01/21/obama-re-takes-oath-of-office-at-the-white-house/|title=Obama re-takes oath of office at the White House|accessdate=2009-02-01|date=2009-01-21|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|work=Political Ticker|author=Mears, Bill}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com/archive/2009/01/20/1751351.aspx|title=About That Oath Flub|accessdate=2009-02-01|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[MSNBC.com]]|author=Montanaro, Domenico }}</ref>

[[File:Second oath of office of Barack Obama.jpg|thumb|left|225px|alt=Obama (right) faces man in judge's robe as they raise their right hands|President Obama (right) retakes the [[Oath of office of the President of the United States|oath of office]] from Chief Justice Roberts at the [[White House]] on January&nbsp;21, 2009. President Obama and Chief Justice Roberts stand near a portrait of [[Benjamin Henry Latrobe]], designer and an early [[Architect of the Capitol]].]]
Roberts ended the presidential oath by appending the phrase "so help you God" to the end of the constitutionally prescribed oath, and Obama responded "[[Oath of office of the President of the United States#"So help me God"|so help me God]]" when he was prompted. Obama had asked previously to include "so help me God" after the oath.<ref name="Mears">{{cite web|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/01/09/obama-to-asked-to-say-so-help-me-god-at-swearing-in/|title=Obama has asked to say 'so help me God' at swearing-in|author=Mears, Bill|work=Political Ticker|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|date=2009-01-09|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref> Roberts then congratulated Obama as the new President.<ref name="oathflub"/>

Much public discussion arose about the missteps in administering and reciting the oath, with one constitutional scholar observing that "it's an open question whether [Obama is] president until he takes the proper oath."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/01/20/MNAF15E20I.DTL|title=Experts say Obama should retake the oath|last=Lochhead|first=Carolyn|date=2009-01-21|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle|San&nbsp;Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=2009-04-28}}</ref> 
Although [[Robert Gibbs]], [[White House press secretary]], indicated at first that President Obama did not plan to retake the oath,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/blogs/2009/01/21/politics/politicalhotsheet/entry4744187.shtml|title=No Plans For Obama To Retake Oath|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=2009-01-21|accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref> Chief Justice Roberts agreed to re<U+2011>administer the oath at the request of [[White House counsel]]. The second oath ceremony took place on the evening of January&nbsp;21, 2009 in the [[Map Room (White House)|Map Room]] of the [[White House]] before a small audience of presidential aides, reporters and a White House photographer.<ref name=NYTretake>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/22/us/politics/22oath.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=oath%20of%20office%20retake&st=cse|title=I Really Do Swear, Faithfully: Obama and Roberts Try Again | author=Zeleny, Jeff|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-01|date=2009-01-21}}</ref> According to White House counsel [[Greg Craig]], the presidential oath was re<U+2011>administered out of an abundance of caution over concerns about the legality of the oath as it was administered by Roberts on Inauguration Day. Craig added that "the oath of office was administered effectively and&nbsp;... the President was sworn in appropriately&nbsp;... But the oath appears in the Constitution itself."<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite news |first=Michael D.|last=Shear|title=Obama sworn in again, with right words|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/21/AR2009012103685.html |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |date=2009-01-22 |accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref> No Bible was present during the retake of the inauguration, which aroused some criticism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article5567187.ece|title=Barack Obama sworn in again, but without a Bible|accessdate=2009-12-11|date=2009-01-22|author=Naughton, Philippe |work=[[The Times]]}}</ref>

====Inaugural address====
A central theme of President Obama's inaugural address was a call to restore responsibility<U+2014>both in terms of accountability in Washington and the responsibility of ordinary people to get involved.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/jan/20/barack-obama-inauguration-us-speech|title=Obama inauguration: Words of history&nbsp;... crafted by 27-year-old in Starbucks|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=[[United Kingdom]]|date=2009-01-20|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/01/18/responsibility-theme-obamas-inauguration-speech-aides-say/|title=Responsibility is the Theme of Obama's Inauguration Speech, Aides Say"|publisher=[[Fox News]]|date=2009-01-18|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref> Obama's address did not have memorable sound bite phrases. Instead, he used traditional references to connect his new administration with the nation's history in a speech that was understated deliberately, according to rhetoric expert James Mackin.<ref name=mackin>{{cite web|url=http://tulane.edu/news/newwave/012309_inaugural_address.cfm|title=Inaugural Speech Focuses on Tradition|work=New Wave|publisher=[[Tulane University]]|date=2009-01-23|accessdate=2009-03-04}}</ref>
{{Listen
 |header=Inaugural Address
 |filename=Barack Obama inaugural address.ogv
 |alt=A black man in a black coat gestures and talks at a lecturn surrounded by teleprompters. Behind him, in the background, are about a dozen warmly-dressed onlookers.
 |title=Inaugural address of Barack Obama
 |description=Barack Obama delivers his [[inaugural address]] on January 20, 2009.<br>(Duration: 21 minutes, 21 seconds)
 |filename2=Barack Obama inauguration speech 2009.ogg 
 |title2=Inaugural address of Barack Obama (audio-only version)
 |description2=Audio version of January 20 address
 |help=no
 |type=sound
}}
Obama concluded the second paragraph of his address by saying, "we the people have remained faithful&nbsp;to&nbsp;the ideals of our forebears and true to our founding documents." The speech reinforced words such as "legacy" and "heritage", as well as values such as "honesty", "courage" and "patriotism", which "are old" values. Near the end of the speech, Obama referred to words written by [[Thomas Paine]] in ''[[The American Crisis]]'', which were ordered by [[George Washington]] to be read to his troops: "Let it be told to the future world&nbsp;... that in the depth of winter, when nothing but hope and virtue could survive&nbsp;... that the city and the country, alarmed at one common danger, came forth to meet [it]." Because Obama's [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2008|campaign]] message focused on the need for change, Mackin noted that Obama sought to reassure Americans that he would operate as President within the margins of the nation's traditions.<ref name=mackin/>

As part of Obama's call for responsibility, he said "what is required of us now is a new era of responsibility<U+2014>a recognition, on the part of every American" and "those of us who manage the public's dollars will be held to account." Obama quoted the lyrics of the [[Jerome Kern]] and [[Dorothy Fields]] song "[[Pick Yourself Up]]" from the [[musical film|musical]] [[comedy film|comedy]] [[Swing Time (1936 film)|''Swing Time'']], saying that "starting today, we must pick ourselves up, dust ourselves off, and begin again the work of remaking America."<ref name="boston_globe">{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/politics/politicalintelligence/2009/01/obama_calls_for_3.html|title=Obama calls for American renewal|author=Foon Rhee|date=2009-01-20|accessdate=2009-03-04|work=[[The Boston Globe|The&nbsp;Boston Globe]]}}</ref> In an article for the ''The New York Times'', columnist and former drama critic [[Frank Rich]] noted the link to the lyric in Field's song from the movie, writing that Obama offered in his address "one subtle whiff of the [[Great Depression]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/25/opinion/25rich.html?em|title=No Time for Poetry|author=Rich, Frank|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|date=2009-01-25|accessdate=2009-01-25|p. WK10 of NY edition.}}</ref>

Obama's speech contained several [[Bible|biblical]] references and was compared to oratory of the "[[black church]] tradition." Obama also highlighted the United States' religious diversity, referring to the country's "patchwork heritage" as a strength and saying, "We are a nation of Christians and Muslims, Jews and Hindus and non-believers." This was the first time a United States President acknowledged [[Irreligion in the United States|American non-believers]] in an inaugural address.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/religion/2009-01-20-obama-non-believers_N.htm|title=An inaugural first: Obama acknowledges 'non-believers'|accessdate=2010-02-02|date=2009-01-22|work=[[USA Today]]|author=Grossman, Cathy Lynn}}</ref>

Obama's inaugural address received mixed reviews, with some describing the tone of the speech a praiseworthy one of restraint and plain speaking,<ref name=WpBOia>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/inauguration/la-na-inaug-literati21-2009jan21,0,7682733.story|title=Writers praise Barack Obama's inaugural address|accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2009-01-21|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Reynolds, Susan Salter}}</ref> while others described the speech as low-brow and cliched.<ref name=OIADSC>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/21/obamas-inaugural-address_n_159713.html|title=Obama's Inaugural Address Draws Some Criticism|accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2009-01-21|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref> Despite his optimism, Obama was critical of former Presidents George&nbsp;W. Bush and [[Bill Clinton|Bill&nbsp;Clinton]].<ref name=WpBOia/> [[David E. Sanger]], chief Washington correspondent for ''[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]'', described the speech as the harshest rebuke of an outgoing President during an inaugural address since [[Franklin Roosevelt]]'s call for restoration of American values.<ref name=RBERV>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/21/us/politics/21assess.html?_r=1|title=Rejecting Bush Era, Reclaiming Values |accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2009-01-20|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Sanger, David}}</ref> The Bush administration was upset about the tone of the speech, saying that the speech veered from that of a ritualistic but respectful thanks to that of a public diatribe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themoderatevoice.com/25881/bush-team-reportedly-irked-over-obama-inaugural-address/|title=Bush Team Reportedly Irked Over Obama Inaugural Address|accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2009-01-23|work=The Moderate Voice|author=Gandelman, Joe}}</ref> Members of the Republican party viewed the speech as a missed chance to seek unity, while [[Rahm Emanuel]], Obama's [[White House Chief of Staff]], described the speech as a reflection of the mandate of the people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/23/us/politics/22web-baker.html|title=On Plane to Texas, Critiques of the Speech |accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2009-01-22|publisher=|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Baker, Peter}}</ref> In an analysis of the inaugural address, one reporter described the speech as one that emphasized the burdens of the moment and the cloudy future whose challenges may be met with the resolve that is part of our American heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Inauguration/story?id=6666797&page=1|title=Obama's Inaugural Address: 'We Must Pick Ourselves Up': President Obama's Inaugural Address Weighted With Expectation and Promise|accessdate=2009-03-07|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>

====Prayers====
Obama's selections of Warren and Lowery to deliver prayers for the inaugural ceremony were controversial. Warren had a history of vocal opposition to [[same-sex marriage]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28733017/|title=Gay rights protest held outside Warren church: Marchers decry pastor's selection as Obama inauguration speaker|accessdate=2009-03-07|date=2009-01-19|publisher=[[MSNBC.com]]}}</ref> and Lowery had a background as a [[civil rights]] activist.<ref name=WLtdib>{{cite web|url=http://ncronline.org/node/2853|title=Warren, Lowery to deliver inauguration blessings |accessdate=2009-03-07|date=2008-12-18|work=[[National Catholic Reporter]]|author=Banks, Adelle M.}}</ref> Neither Obama nor Warren made references during the inaugural program to issues of direct concern to the gay community. In the invocation, Warren asked for "forgiveness for Americans 'when we fight each other' and 'civility in our attitudes even when we differ.'"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasvoice.com/artman/publish/article_10496.php|title=Obama doesn<U+2019>t mention gays in Inaugural address, but LGBT community more visible than ever in D.C.|accessdate=2009-03-07|date=2009-01-22|work=[[Dallas Voice]]|author=Keen, Lisa}}</ref> Warren mentioned Dr.&nbsp;Martin&nbsp;Luther King and Jesus in the invocation, and he concluded the invocation with the [[Lord's Prayer]].<ref name=LB/> Lowery used both humor and sincerity as he delivered the benediction.  One of his sincere messages was the statement that "as we leave this mountaintop, help us to hold on to the spirit of fellowship and the oneness of our family." Lowery concluded the benediction with a humorous message of anticipation for the day "when [[Brown people|brown]] can stick around, when [[Mongoloid race|yellow]] will be mellow, when the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|red man]] can get ahead man and when [[Caucasian race|white]] would embrace what is right".<ref name=LB/> Conservatives, including [[Rush Limbaugh]] decried Lowery's benediction, which quoted from "[[Lift Every Voice and Sing]]" (the "Black National Anthem"), as racist,<ref name=LB/><ref name=IpspOs>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldnetdaily.com/index.php?fa=PAGE.view&pageId=86675|title=Inaugural prayer slam prompts Obama smile: Rush Limbaugh: Lowery 'just insulted this country'|accessdate=2009-03-07|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[WorldNetDaily]]|author=Schilling, Chelsea}}</ref> while Democrats disagreed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressreleasepoint.com/viewers-offer-mixed-reactions-reverend-lowery039s-inaugural-benediction|title=Viewers Offer Mixed Reactions to Reverend Lowery's Inaugural Benediction|accessdate=2009-03-07|date=2009-01-26|publisher=HCD Research|author=}}</ref> Another of Lowery's rhymes, "When [[African American|black]] will not be asked to get in back",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2009/01/when_black_will_not_be_asked_t.cfm|title=When black will not be asked to get back|date=2009-01-21|publisher=[[The Economist]]|accessdate=2009-06-18}}</ref> particularly offended the likes of Limbaugh who felt that Obama's ascension on that day symbolized the fact that America had come to that point already.<ref name=IpspOs/>

===Post-ceremony traditions===
[[File:George W. Bush in Marine One.jpg|thumb|[[George W. Bush]] looks at the [[U.S. Capitol]] as he is departing on [[Marine One]] after the Inauguration.|alt=George W. Bush wearing a suit, tie, scarf and overcoat while looking out the window from a skyward vehicle.]]
After the inaugural ceremony, President Obama, [[First Lady]] Michelle Obama, Vice President Joe Biden and Dr. Jill Biden escorted former President [[George W. Bush]] and former First Lady [[Laura Bush]] to a departure ceremony on the east side of the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol. Before the luncheon and in keeping with tradition, President Obama signed his first [[Executive order (United States)|presidential orders]] in the President's Room at the Capitol,<ref name=Osfpp/> and then signed the guest book for the luncheon.<ref name=LB/> The first order signed by Obama was a proclamation declaring his Inauguration Day a "National Day of Renewal and Reconciliation",<ref name=Osfpp/> in which he called "upon all of our citizens to serve one another and the common purpose of remaking this Nation for our new century".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catholic.org/national/national_story.php?id=31715|title=President Obama's First Presidential Proclamation|date=2009-01-21|accessdate=2010-02-07|publisher=Catholic Online}}</ref> Obama signed orders to officially present the nominations for his [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]] and several sub<U+2011>Cabinet officials to the U.S.&nbsp;Congress for its approval.<ref name=Osfpp>{{cite web|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/01/20/obama-signs-first-presidential-proclamation/|title=Obama signs first presidential proclamation|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|date=2009-01-20|accessdate=2009-03-26}}</ref> The Obamas and Bidens then attended an inaugural luncheon at the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol before traveling from there to the presidential reviewing stand at the White House to watch the parade.

====Luncheon====
As former President and Mrs. Bush began their journey to their [[Texas]] home, the Obamas and Bidens joined several congressional guests for the inaugural luncheon in [[National Statuary Hall]] at the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol. Guests included top Washington lawmakers as well as former Presidents and Vice Presidents. Commemorating the [[Abraham Lincoln Bicentennial]], the red and white china used during the luncheon were [[replica]]s of those used in the Lincoln White House.<ref name=thehill>{{cite news |first=Mike|last=Soraghan|title=Obama's Inauguration makes tourists out of lawmakers |url=http://thehill.com/leading-the-news/obamas-inauguration-makes-tourists-out-of-lawmakers-2009-01-20.html |work= [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |publisher=|date=2009-01-20 |accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref>

[[File:2009 Obama inauguration luncheon.jpg|thumb|left|225px|alt=Barack Obama addresses attendees at an indoor ceremony|Obama addresses the luncheon attendees in [[National Statuary Hall]] at the [[United States Capitol|U.S.&nbsp;Capitol]].]]
A luncheon at the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol has been part of the inaugural program since 1953 (before that time, the luncheon was usually held at the White House and hosted by the outgoing President and First Lady). The menu for the 2009 inaugural luncheon, which often features dishes representative of the home states of the new President and Vice President, included seafood stew, duck and [[pheasant]] entrees with [[Pinot noir]] wine, and a dessert of apple cinnamon [[sponge cake]] with sweet cream [[Candied fruit|glac<U+00E9>]]. Since 1985, a painting has served as a backdrop for the head table. For the 2009 inaugural luncheon, the featured painting was [[Thomas Hill (painter)|Thomas Hill's]] 1865 ''View of the Yosemite Valley'', a painting that commemorated Abraham Lincoln's 1864 signing of the [[Yosemite National Park#Yosemite Grant|Yosemite Grant]], which was the first time the federal government protected park lands for public use.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inaugural.senate.gov/luncheon/|title= Inauguration of the President: Luncheon|publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]]|accessdate=2009-02-16}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://inaugural.senate.gov/history/daysevents/inauguralluncheon.cfm|title= Inaugural Luncheon|publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]]|accessdate=2009-02-16}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://inaugural.senate.gov/luncheon/painting.cfm|title= 2009 Painting: <U+2018>View of the Yosemite Valley<U+2019>|publisher=[[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|United States Congress Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]]|accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref>

During the luncheon, Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] collapsed after suffering a [[Non-epileptic seizure|seizure]], and he was transported to a hospital for medical treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28755439/|title=Kennedy released from hospital after seizure: Aide: His spirits are good; doctors want him to get some rest|publisher=|work=[[MSNBC.com]]|date=2009-01-21|accessdate=2009-02-09}}</ref><ref name=SKCALFO>{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=99614326|title=Sen. Kennedy Collapses At Luncheon For Obama|accessdate=2009-02-090|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]}}</ref> Early reports about the medical emergency suggested erroneously that Senator [[Robert Byrd]], the oldest member of the Senate, also fell ill during the luncheon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24942005-5006506,00.html|title=Ted Kennedy collapses at inauguration|accessdate=2009-02-09|date=2009-01-20|publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|The Daily Telegraph]]'' (Australia)}}</ref> These reports were later denied,<ref name=SKCALFO/> and Byrd, a longtime friend of Kennedy, eventually explained that the Kennedy incident disturbed him and caused him to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/20/ted-kennedy-collapsed-at_n_159415.html|title=Ted Kennedy Collapsed At Obama Inaugural Luncheon|accessdate=2009-02-09|date=2009-01-20|work=[[The Huffington Post]]}}</ref>

====Parade====
{{Further|[[:File:2009 Inaugural Parade Route.png|2009 Inaugural parade route]]}}

[[File:Obamas walk down PA Ave. 1-20-09 hires 090120-N-0696M-546a.jpg|thumb|225px|alt=Barack and Michelle Obama acknowledge the crowd while the Secret Service and onlookers watch.|President Obama and [[First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]] walking the inaugural parade route]]
The inaugural parade route ran along [[Pennsylvania Avenue]],&nbsp;[[Northwest, Washington, D.C.|N.W.]] from the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol, ending at the north face of the White House. During most of the parade, President Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama traveled in the new armored [[Presidential State Car (United States)|limousine]] because of potential security threats.<ref name=parade>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24942113-5015669,00.html|title=In a New Tux, Obama Seeks the Proper Tone|accessdate=2009-01-24|date=2009-01-21|publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|The Daily Telegraph]]'' (Australia)|author=}}</ref> The President and First Lady twice exited their limousine,  walking on Pennsylvania Avenue for portions of the parade.<ref>Lawrence, J. (2009-01-20). [http://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2009-01-20-parade_N.htm An inaugural parade they won't soon forget.] ''[[USAToday]]''. Retrieved 2009-01-28.</ref> Vice President Biden and his wife Jill walked the parade route at several points with their children [[Beau Biden|Beau]], Hunter and Ashley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%20125E199E22E82C28%20)&p_docid=125E199E22E82C28&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=125E199E22E82C28&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=T5FL5CQWMTI0MTc5MTM2My4xNzE0MTI6MToxMDoxMjguMTIuMC4w&&p_multi=NWJB|title=Capping a long career, Biden 's swearing-in a climactic moment for Del.'s leading man |accessdate=2009-04-12|date=2009-01-21|work=[[The News Journal]]|location=[[Wilmington, Delaware|Wilmington, DE]])|author=Gaudiano, Nicole}}</ref>

The parade lasted more than two hours during the afternoon and early evening following the inaugural ceremony. Parade participants included 15,000&nbsp;people, 240&nbsp;horses, dozens of marching bands, two drum and bugle corps and a [[mariachi]] band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sunday-star-times/features/799447|title=Tradition and hoopla for Obama's big day|accessdate=2010-02-07|date=2009-01-20|work=[[Sunday Star Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/worldnews/article-1099445/Obamas-inauguration-cost-20m-authorities-battle-cope-massive-influx-wishers.html|title=Obama's inauguration to cost <U+00A3>20m as authorities battle to cope with massive influx of well-wishers|accessdate=2009-02-09|date=2008-12-21|work=[[Daily Mail]]|location=[[United Kingdom]]|author=Thompson, Paul}}</ref><ref name=OsflOip/> President Obama invited the [[Virginia Military Institute]]&nbsp;corps of cadets, [[Drum Corps International]], [[The Cadets Drum and Bugle Corps|Cadets Drum and Bugle Corps]], [[Colts Drum and Bugle Corps]] from {{city-state|Dubuque|Iowa}}. Obama invited the marching band from [[Punahou School]], his high school in Hawaii, to perform in the parade along with the marching unit of its [[Junior Reserve Officers' Training Corps]].<ref name=IaNTOStPT>{{cite web|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9804E6D81E39F93AA35751C1A96E9C8B63|title=In a New Tux, Obama Seeks the Proper Tone|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-12-09|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Seelye, Katharine Q.}}</ref>

Vice President Joe Biden invited several groups from Delaware to march in the parade. The Delaware section was led by the [[Delaware Volunteer Firemen's Association]] of which Biden is an honorary member, the Fightin' Blue Hen Marching Band, The Pride of Delaware, from Biden's alma mater, the [[University of Delaware]],<ref name="parades">{{cite news|url=http://chicago.about.com/od/parades/a/InauguralParade.htm|title=Inauguration Parade 2009 <U+2013> Overview and List of Participants: The 56th Inaugural Parade|last=Roche|first=Jennifer|date=2009|publisher=About.com|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref> and the [[Delaware State University]] Hornets Approaching Storm marching band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.desu.edu/advancement/pr/press_release.php?article_id=479|title=DSU Band to Perform Jan. 18 Pre-Inaugural Concert|date=2009-01-07|publisher=[[Delaware State University]]|accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/blogs/paper-trail/2009/01/21/black-colleges-well-represented-at-inaugural-parade.html|title=Black Colleges Well Represented at Inaugural Parade|accessdate=2010-02-07|date=2009-01-21|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]]}}</ref>

====Inaugural balls====

President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama attended 10 official inaugural balls during the evening of January&nbsp;20, 2009.<ref>
{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20081224/inaugural_balls_081224/20081224?hub=Politics|title=Obamas to twirl through 10 inaugural balls January 20|accessdate=2009-02-13|date=2008-12-24|publisher=[[CTV Television Network]] (Canada)}}
</ref><ref name=wbz>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Schedule Of Inaugural Events And Balls |url=http://wbztv.com/politics/Inauguration.events.schedule.2.911862.html |publisher= [[WBZ-TV]]|date=2009-01-19 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref> Barack Obama wore a new [[Black tie|tuxedo]] made by [[Hart Schaffner Marx]], a [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]-based menswear company.<ref name=IaNTOStPT/> Michelle Obama wore a white, one-shouldered, sleeveless gown designed by 26&nbsp;year-old [[Manhattan|New&nbsp;York]]-based designer [[Jason Wu|Jason&nbsp;Wu]], breaking with the recent practice set by former first ladies Laura Bush and [[Hillary Clinton]], who showcased designers from their hometowns.<ref>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=All hail the leader of the fashionable world |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2009/01/20/ST2009012004580.html |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref>

'''The Neighborhood Inaugural Ball''', one of six balls held at the [[Walter E. Washington Convention Center]], was the first stop of the evening for the President and First Lady. The Obamas danced their first song as [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]] serenaded them with her rendition of the [[Etta James]] classic, ''[[At Last]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Obamas dance, celebrate at inaugural balls |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/20/inauguration.balls |publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref> According to the Presidential Inaugural Committee, the Neighborhood Inaugural Ball was the first ball ever with free or affordable tickets, a contrast to recent history in which "inaugural balls generally have been closed to everyday Americans, populated instead by an exclusive circle of dignitaries and donors."<ref>{{cite news |first=Leaman|last=Amy|title=Obama to Host Virtual Ball |url=http://www.washingtonian.com/blogarticles/people/capitalcomment/10726.html|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian Magazine]]|date=2009-01-05 |accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref> A portion of the tickets for the ball was reserved for Washington D.C. residents.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/travel/content/travel/otherdestinations/us_stories/2009/01/05/obama_neighborhood_ball.html|title=Obama adds <U+2018>Neighborhood Ball<U+2019> for D.C. residents|date=2009-01-05|work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|accessdate=2009-05-04}}</ref> 

The nine other official inaugural balls attended by the Obamas that evening included:<ref name=wbz/>

{{multiple image
 | align     = right
 | direction = horizontal
 | header    = The Obamas and Bidens at the<br>President Obama Home States<br>Inaugural Ball
 | header_align = center
