 | footer_align = left/right/center
 | footer_background = 
 | width     = 
 | image1    = Barack and Michelle Obama at the Home States Ball.jpg
 | width1    = 146
 | caption1  = 
 | alt1      =Barack and Michelle Obama dancing arm-in-arm and smiling.  She is wearing a white dress, large ring, long earrings and a bracelet. He is wearing a black tuxedo.
 | image2    = 20090120 Jill and Joe Biden at Homestates Ball.JPG
 | width2    = 115
 | alt2      =A Caucasian man in a tuxedo dancing with a blonde woman in a red dress
}}
*'''The Commander-in-Chief's Ball''', [[National Building Museum]], held only for the second time, included active and reserve duty members of the [[U.S. military|United States military]], the families of American service members currently deployed overseas, the families of military personnel killed in action and recipients of the [[Purple Heart]].<ref name=wbz/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/01/01/obama-to-host-commander-in-chiefs-ball/|title=Obama to host Commander-in-Chief's ball|accessdate=2009-02-09|date=2009-01-01|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]}}</ref><ref name=nydailynews>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Obama announces inauguration Commander in Chief's Ball for war heroes |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2009/01/01/2009-01-01_obama_announces_inauguration_commander_i.html |agency= [[Associated Press]] |work=[[The New York Daily News]] |date=2009-01-01 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref>
*'''The Eastern Ball''', [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]], held for guests from the [[New England|New England states]] of [[Connecticut]], [[Maine]], [[Massachusetts]], [[New Hampshire]], [[Rhode Island]] and [[Vermont]] and the Atlantic territories of [[Puerto Rico]] and the [[United States Virgin Islands|U.S.&nbsp;Virgin Islands]]. [[James Taylor]] performed for guests attending the ball.<ref name=wbz/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/politics/politicalintelligence/2009/01/james_taylor_ge.html|title=James Taylor gets top billing at Eastern ball|accessdate=2009-02-09|2009-01-15|work=[[The Boston Globe|The&nbsp;Boston Globe]]|author=Rhee, Foon}}</ref>
*'''The Mid-Atlantic Ball''', Washington Convention Center, held for guests from the [[District of Columbia]] and the [[Mid-Atlantic States|Mid-Atlantic states]] of Maryland, [[New York]], [[New Jersey]], Virginia and [[West Virginia]]. This ball featured the first 2009 appearance by [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]].<ref name=wbz/>
*'''The Midwestern Ball''', Washington Convention Center, held for guests from the [[Midwestern United States|Midwestern states]] of [[Indiana]], [[Iowa]], [[Kansas]], [[Michigan]], [[Minnesota]], [[Missouri]], [[North Dakota]], [[Nebraska]], [[Ohio]], [[South Dakota]] and [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=wbz/>
*'''The President Obama Home States Ball''', Washington Convention Center, for guests from Barack Obama's home states of Hawaii and Illinois.<ref name=wbz/>
*'''The Southern Ball''', [[D.C. Armory]], held for guests from the [[Southern United States|Southern states]] of [[Alabama]], [[Arkansas]], [[Florida]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Kentucky]], [[Louisiana]], [[Mississippi]], [[North Carolina]], [[South Carolina]], [[Tennessee]] and Texas.<ref name=wbz/>
*'''The Vice President Biden Home States Ball''', Washington Convention Center, for guests from Joe Biden's home states of Delaware and Pennsylvania.<ref name=wbz/>
*'''The Western Ball''', Washington Convention Center, for guests from the [[Western United States|Western states]] of [[Alaska]], [[Arizona]], California, [[Idaho]], [[Colorado]], [[Montana]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Oregon]], [[Nevada]], [[New Mexico]], [[Utah]], [[Washington]] and [[Wyoming]], and the Pacific territories of [[American Samoa]] and [[Guam]].<ref name=wbz/>
*'''The Youth Ball''', [[Hilton Washington|Washington Hilton and Towers]], an event held specifically for guests between the ages of 18 and 35 years old.<ref name=wbz/>

President Obama and the First Lady also attended one inaugural ball during the evening of January&nbsp;21, 2009.

*'''The Obama for America Staff Ball''', [[D.C. Armory]], held for staff members of President Obama's 2008 presidential campaign. The ball featured speeches by [[David Plouffe]], Joe Biden and Barack Obama, as well as a performance by [[Jay-Z]].<ref>{{cite news |first=David A.|last=Nakamura|title=Obama for America Staff Ball right now featuring Jay-Z |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/2009/01/obama_staff_party_right_now_fe.html |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2009-03-02}}</ref>

After they made their formal visits to the circuit of January 20 inaugural balls, the Obamas hosted an after-midnight gathering at the White House for 70&nbsp;of their earliest supporters, close friends and family. Guests who attended the after hours celebration at the White House included [[Oprah Winfrey]], [[Valerie Jarrett]], [[David Axelrod (political consultant)|David Axelrod]], Chicago Mayor [[Richard M. Daley|Richard Daley]], Representatives [[Artur Davis]] of the state of Alabama and [[Neil Abercrombie]] of the state of Hawaii, and Michelle Obama's brother [[Craig Robinson (basketball coach)|Craig Robinson]]. Members of the Illinois congressional delegation also attended the after hours event, including Senator&nbsp;[[Dick Durbin]] and Representatives&nbsp;[[Melissa Bean]], [[Jan Schakowsky]], [[Luis Gutierrez]] and [[Jerry Costello]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Lynn|last=Sweet|title=Obamas throw "late night" gathering after balls in the White House. Oprah, Mayor Daley, among those present |url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2009/01/obamas_throw_late_night_gather.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Dan|last=Nakaso|title=Abercrombie joins Obama at last party |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%20125ECF848009A0D8%20)&p_docid=125ECF848009A0D8&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=125ECF848009A0D8&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=H4BU48FCMTI0MTc5MDY1MC4xMTE0NDk6MToxMDoxMjguMTIuMC4w&&p_multi=HNAB|publisher=[[NewsBank]]|work=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]] |date=2009-01-22 |accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref>

====National prayer service====
On January 21, 2009, President&nbsp;Obama, First&nbsp;Lady Michelle Obama, Vice President Biden and his wife, Dr.&nbsp;Jill Biden, gathered at the [[Washington National Cathedral]] for a national day of prayer.<ref name=prayservice>{{cite web| url=http://www.usnews.com/articles/news/obama/2009/01/21/for-president-obama-a-somber-inclusive-inaugural-prayer-service.html| first=Amanda |last=Ruggeri |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] | title= For President Obama, a Somber, Inclusive Inaugural Prayer Service| date = 2009-01-21 | accessdate= 2009-05-04}}
</ref> At the prayer service, the Obamas and Bidens were joined in the front pew by former President Bill Clinton and his wife, Hillary Clinton, who was sworn in as [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] later that day.<ref name=prayservice/><ref name=OHFFDOTSC>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/22/us/politics/22obamacnd.html|title=On His First Full Day, Obama Tackles Sobering Challenges|accessdate=2009-01-28|date=2009-01-21|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Knowlton, Brian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/21/clinton.confirmation/index.html|title=Hillary Clinton sworn in as secretary of state|date=2009-01-22|publisher=[[CNN|Cable News Network]]|accessdate=2009-05-01}}</ref> The prayer service was attended by about 3,200&nbsp;other invited guests, including members of the U.S.&nbsp;Congress, diplomats and other dignitaries.<ref name="prayersvc">{{cite news|author=Boorstein, Michelle | date=2009-01-22 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/21/AR2009012101029.html |title=Variety of clergy, worship program reflect a focus on inclusiveness| work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref>

[[File:National Prayer Service Obama Inauguration.jpg|thumb|170px|right|alt=From left to right: the Obamas, and two other couples stand with their heads bowed in a pew|From left to right: the Obamas, Bidens and Clintons in the front pew at the Washington National Cathedral on January&nbsp;21, 2009]]
The theme of the interfaith worship service reflected inclusiveness and religious diversity, with a mix of [[Protestantism|Protestant]] pastors, female [[Hinduism|Hindu]] and [[Muslim]] religious leaders, rabbis and [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] bishops who delivered scripture readings and prayers throughout the service. Prayers for the service drew from passages from the [[First inauguration of George Washington|1789 inauguration]] prayer service of George Washington and the 1865&nbsp;inaugural address of Abraham Lincoln, including phrases such as "with malice toward none, with charity for all".<ref name="prayersvc"/> The featured sermon for the inaugural prayer service was delivered by Reverend Sharon&nbsp;E. Watkins, general minister and president of the [[Christian Church (Disciples of Christ)]] and the first woman to deliver the sermon for the inaugural prayer service.<ref>{{cite news |first=Laurie |last=Goodstein|title=Obama Names Minister to Lead Prayer Service|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/11/us/politics/11minister.html|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|date=2009-01-10 |accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref> In her sermon, Watkins integrated passages from a variety of sources, such as passages summoned from sources rooted in the Hindu, [[Judaism|Jewish]], Muslim and [[Cherokee]] faiths.<ref name="prayersvc"/>

==Unofficial events==
{{main|List of unofficial events for the inauguration of Barack Obama}}

In addition to the official events, groups and supporters held an array of gatherings and celebrations throughout Washington,&nbsp;D.C. and the surrounding region in the days before and the evening following the inauguration.<ref name="schedule">{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Obama Inauguration Schedule |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/14/obama-inauguration-schedu_0_n_157859.html |agency=[[Associated Press]] |work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=2009-01-24 |accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref> One such event, a newly created "People's Inaugural Ball" was held for economically and physically disadvantaged people from across the United States who otherwise would be unable to afford to attend the inaugural festivities.<ref name=wp2>{{cite news |first=Avis|last=Thomas-Lester|title=Preparing for the Ball of a Lifetime |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2009/01/19/ST2009011900765.html |work= [[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |date=2009-01-01 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref> Earl&nbsp;W. Stafford, a businessman from [[Fairfax County, Virginia|Fairfax County]], Virginia, spent an estimated $1.6&nbsp;million dollars through his family's foundation to bring approximately 300&nbsp;guests to Washington,&nbsp;D.C., hosting the ball on January&nbsp;19, 2009 for a total of about 450&nbsp;people.<ref name=wp2/><ref>{{cite web|author=Thomas-Lester, Avis|date=2009-01-21|accessdate=2009-02-13|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/20/AR2009012004154_2.html?sid=ST2009012003848&s_pos=|title=Businessman's gift stirs "platinum-level guests."|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]}}</ref> Clothing, shoes, tuxedos and hotel rooms for attendees were provided as part of the invitation.<ref name=afpgoogle>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Fairy godfather invites disadvantaged to inaugural ball |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5g286yHHwAWCcEyaqMWnkqYgOUZOw |publisher= [[Agence France-Presse]] |date=2009-01-19 |accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref>

==Attendance==
===Dignitaries, family and celebrity guests===
Former Presidents [[Jimmy Carter]], [[George H.W. Bush]], [[Bill Clinton]] and [[George W. Bush]] and former Vice Presidents [[Walter Mondale]], [[Dan Quayle]], [[Al Gore|Al&nbsp;Gore]] and Dick&nbsp;Cheney, along with their wives, attended the inauguration.<ref name=guests>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Obama sworn-in as 44th&nbsp;US President: Challenges real, but 'they will be met.' |url=http://nation.ittefaq.com/issues/2009/01/21/news0184.htm |work=The New Nation|location=[[Bangladesh]] |date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2009-01-21}}</ref><ref name=Cafiiw>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Cheney to Use Wheelchair Today After Hurting Back While Moving|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/19/AR2009011903428.html|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |date=2009-01-20 |accessdate=2009-03-02}}</ref> Cheney was [[wheelchair]]-bound because of an injury that he suffered while moving boxes.<ref name=Cafiiw/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usnews.com/blogs/planning-to-retire/2009/01/20/cheney-in-wheelchair-for-inauguration-ceremony.html|title=Cheney in Wheelchair for Inauguration Ceremony|accessdate=2009-02-08|date=2009-01-20|work=[[U.S.News & World Report]]|author=Brandon, Emily}}</ref> 

[[John Lewis (Georgia)|John Lewis]], the only living speaker from the historic 1963&nbsp;rally at the [[March on Washington]], was present on the stage during the inauguration.<ref name=The_New_Yorker>{{cite web|accessdate=2009-03-06
|url=http://www.newyorker.com/talk/comment/2009/02/02/090202taco_talk_remnick|title=The President's Hero |date=2008-02-02
|author=Remnick, David |work=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref> More than 180 of the [[Tuskegee Airmen]] attended as invited guests for the inauguration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/10/us/politics/10inaug.html|title=Inauguration Is a Culmination for Black Airmen |accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-12-09|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Seelye, Katharine Q.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123131934|title=Inauguration brings Tuskegee Airmen to Bolling|accessdate=2009-03-06|date=2009-01-20|publisher=[[United States Air Force]]|author=Longoria, R. Michael}}</ref> The five-person crew of [[US Airways Flight 1549|US&nbsp;Airways Flight&nbsp;1549]] attended the swearing-in ceremony, including [[Chesley Sullenberger]], the pilot who [[Water_landing#Commercial_aircraft|landed]] the aircraft in the [[Hudson River]] near [[Manhattan]] after losing both engines due to a [[bird strike]] just after departing [[LaGuardia Airport]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Katharine Q. |last=Seelye |title=Obama Invites Flight 1549 Pilot and Crew to Inauguration |url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/19/obama-invites-flight-1549-pilot-and-crew-to-inauguration |work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]] |date=2009-01-19 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref>

Eighty-seven year old [[Sarah Onyango Obama|Sarah Obama]] led a group of Obama's [[Kenya]]n relatives from his father's home village of [[Kogelo]].<ref name=washingtontimes>{{cite news |first=|last=|title= Embassy Row: Obama's Grandma|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/jan/07/embassy-row-54767307/ |work= [[The Washington Times|The&nbsp;Washington Times]] |publisher= |date=2009-01-07 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref> Other relatives who traveled from Kenya as guests included Obama's aunt, Maggie Obama, his uncle, [[Said Obama]], as well as his half-brother [[Malik Obama]].<ref name=washingtontimes/><ref name=iol>{{cite news |first=|last=|title= Obama's gran brings traditional gifts|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=3&art_id=vn20090118075407893C127411 |work= [[Independent Online (South Africa)]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |date=2009-01-18 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref>  Joe Biden's son, Beau, [[Delaware Attorney General|Attorney General for the state of Delaware]] and an officer and [[Judge Advocate General's Corps|Judge Advocate]] in the [[Delaware Army National Guard]], received a special furlough from serving in [[Iraq War|Iraq]] to participate in the ceremonies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/01/16/bidens-son-leaves-iraq-for-inauguration/|title=Biden's son back from Iraq for the inauguration|accessdate=2009-02-09|date=2009-01-15|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]}}</ref>

Celebrity guests included the actors [[Dustin Hoffman]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Tom Hanks]] and [[Denzel Washington]], talk show host [[Oprah Winfrey]] and director [[Steven Spielberg]].<ref name=guests/>

===Crowds and general ticket holders===
[[File:Crowd at National Mall for Obama inauguration 1-20-09 hires 090120-F-6184M-007a.jpg|thumb|245px|alt=View of the entire length of the National Mall and the Washington Monument with a large audience of attendees|Crowds watch the inauguration at the [[National Mall]]. The [[Washington Monument]], and the [[Lincoln Memorial]] behind it, are in the background.]]
No official count was taken of the number of people attending the inaugural ceremony, although multiple sources concluded that the ceremony had the largest audience of an event ever held in Washington,&nbsp;D.C. Government agencies and federal officials, who coordinated security and traffic management, determined the attendance count to be 1.8&nbsp;million people based on information collected by several cameras and individuals on the ground. ''[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]'' reported the estimated crowd size for the inaugural ceremony, and the [[National Park Service]] said it did not contest the estimate.<ref name="Washington Post">{{cite-news | last=Ruane | first=Michael | title=D.C.'s Inauguration Head Count: 1.8 Million | accessdate= 2009-01-22|date= 2009-01-20| work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] | url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/21/AR2009012103884.html}}</ref><ref name="bostonglobe-attendance">{{cite-news | last= | first= | title=Inaugural crowd size reportedly D.C. record | accessdate= 2009-01-22|date= 2009-01-22| work=[[The Boston Globe|The&nbsp;Boston Globe]] | url = http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2009/01/22/inaugural_crowd_size_reportedly_dc_record/}}</ref>

Stephen Doig, a professor at [[Arizona State University]], estimated that 800,000&nbsp;people attended the inauguration ceremony using the same satellite image. Although the image was taken a little less than 45&nbsp;minutes before Obama<U+2019>s swearing-in ceremony, Doig adjusted his estimate to include people who were still arriving in the area before the event.<ref name="ASU">{{cite news | first=Griselda | last=Nevarez | coauthors= | title= Professor estimates crowds with satellite image | date= 2009-01-21 | publisher= [[Arizona State University]] | url = http://www.asuwebdevil.com/node/3654 | work = | page = | accessdate = 2009-01-22}}</ref> In spite of his crowd estimate, Doig stated that "if I had to bet, I would say the [Barack] Obama crowd is in fact bigger than those that showed up for [Johnson] or any of the other things"&nbsp;... "I'm wholly prepared to think it was the largest crowd."<ref name="Washington Post"/> Approximately 1.2&nbsp;million people had attended the [[second inauguration of Lyndon B. Johnson]] in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jan/21/nation/na-inaug-crowds21|title=A record crowd for inauguration? Hard to say |accessdate=2009-02-09| date=2009-01-20| work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Levey, Noam N.}}</ref>

Amid the massive crowds that arrived at the U.S.&nbsp;Capitol for the inauguration, about 4,000&nbsp;ticket holders were unable to gain entry to reserved areas on the Capitol grounds after security personnel closed the gates at the start of the formal ceremony. Many ticket holders were stuck in underground tunnels where pedestrian traffic was directed to and from the [[National Mall]], while others remained stuck in long lines as they waited to gain entry to the reserved areas.<ref name="WP-Constable-Too Late-2009-01-21">
{{cite news |last = Constable | first = Pamela | coauthors =  Mary Beth Sheridan |title='And Then We Knew It Was Too Late' |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]  | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/20/AR2009012003362.html?hpid=topnews |date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2009-01-22}}
</ref><ref name = "WP-Carliner-Purple-2009-01-22">
{{cite news |title=Purple, Silver, Blue Ticket Holders Turned Away |first=Leah |last=Carliner |date=January 20, 2009 |accessdate=January 22, 2009 |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]  |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/2009/01/people_with_tickets_being_turn.html?hpid=topnews }}
</ref><ref name="WP-Carliner-Photos-2009-01-22">
{{cite news |title=User Photos of D St. Problems, Crowds |first=Leah |last=Carliner |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |date=January 20, 2009 |accessdate=January 22, 2009 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/2009/01/user_photos_of_d_st_problems_c.html }}
</ref><ref name="WP-Constable-Ticket Troubles-2009-01-21">
{{cite news |title=Ticket and Travel Troubles Cloud Inauguration Success |date=January 22, 2009 |accessdate=January 22, 2009 |last=Constable |first=Pamela; Sheridan, Mary Beth |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |page=A01 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/21/AR2009012104248.html?sid=ST2009012003386&s_pos= }}
</ref> Senator Dianne Feinstein, in her capacity as chair of the Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies, launched an investigation to address complaints by the affected ticket holders.<ref name="WP-Nakamura-2009-02-21">
{{cite news |title=Sen. Feinstein Launches Investigation into Ticket Fiasco |first= David A. |last=Nakamura |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |date=January 21, 2009 |accessdate=January 21, 2009 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/inauguration-watch/2009/01/sen_feinstein_launches_investi.html }}
</ref> The committee later announced that ticket holders who were unable to enter the Capitol grounds to view the ceremony would receive a copy of the swearing-in invitation and program, photos of President Obama and Vice President Biden, and a color print of the inaugural ceremony.<ref name = "Blocked-ticketholders">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/No-Consolation-Blocked-Ticket-Holders-Get-Parting-Gifts.html|title=No Consolation: Parting gifts for blocked ticket holders|last=Stabley|first=Matthew|date=2009-28|publisher=[[WRC-TV]] (Washington,&nbsp;D.C.)|accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>

===Security===
The inauguration took place in an era of enhanced security in the decade following the [[September 11 attacks]]. Because of the size of the crowds expected in Washington,&nbsp;D.C. for the inaugural activities, planners raised concerns about public safety and security. [[U.S. Army|Army]] [[General (United States)|General]] Richard Rowe, head of the joint military task force for the Washington, D.C. area, explained that security forces had to stretch their imagination to anticipate previously unthinkable security threats, especially in light of the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Mumbai attacks]] in [[India]] that occurred in November 2008.<ref>{{cite news|http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/01/19/2469096.htm|title=Obama security team 'prepared for unthinkable'|date=2009-01-19|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|Australian Broadcasting News]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref>  Attention was heightened by terrorist threats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/17/magazine/17Terror-t.html?ref=magazine|title=Obama<U+2019>s War Over Terror |author=Baker, Peter|accessdate=2010-01-18|date=2009-01-04|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>

[[File:National Guard at 2009 Inauguration.JPG|thumb|left|235px|alt=Military personnel and vehicle in the street|[[National Guard of the United States|U.S. National Guard]] vehicle on [[K Street (Washington, D.C.)|K&nbsp;Street,&nbsp;N.W.]] in Washington,&nbsp;D.C. during the inauguration]]
The police presence in the District of Columbia temporarily doubled, augmented by the addition of 8,000&nbsp;police officers from around the United States. The police force was assisted by 1,000&nbsp;[[FBI]] agents to provide security for the event,<ref name=SCEBHfIaBI/><ref name=OsflOip>
{{cite news|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jAxfsUb6KLjwIDSt0zMbKoKfqncA |title=Officials scramble for last-minute Obama inauguration plans|accessdate=2008-12-21|date=2008-12-21|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}
</ref> and the [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] [[Countersniper]] team was assigned to hidden locations throughout the area.<ref name=CNN>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/US/01/19/sniper.training/|title=Secret Service countersnipers hunt for real snipers|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|date=2009-01-19|accessdate=2009-03-04|author=Meserve, Jeanne and Mike M. Ahlers}}</ref> The [[Transportation Security Administration]] had over 300 officers from its National Deployment Force on hand to assist the Secret Service with security inspections of attendees entering the National Mall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tsa.gov/press/happenings/2009_inauguration.shtm|title=TSA Helps Secure Inauguration|accessdate=2009-04-03|date=2009-01-21|publisher=[[Transportation Security Administration|U.S. Transportation Security Administration]]/[[U.S. Department of Homeland Security|U.S.&nbsp;Department of Homeland Security]]}}</ref> Ten thousand [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops were on site, with 5,000&nbsp;troops providing security duty in a ceremonial capacity and 1,300&nbsp;unarmed troops aiding [[United States Park Police|Park Police]] in crowd control at the National Mall. C&nbsp;Company of the 1-175&nbsp;[[Infantry]] provided security between the first and second public viewing areas of the National Mall at the 7th&nbsp;Street,&nbsp;N.W. intersection, while the remaining members performed other security functions.<ref name=Ostrrthi/> Because the Secret Service declared the Obama inauguration a special [[national security]] event, the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] implemented additional airspace restrictions over Washington,&nbsp;D.C. between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 6:00&nbsp;p.m. on January&nbsp;20, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.faa.gov/news/media/public_advisory_inauguration_2009.pdf |title=Flight Advisory National Security Event: 2009 Presidential Pre-Inauguration Festivities|date=2009|publisher=[[Federal Aviation Administration|U.S.&nbsp;Federal Aviation Administration]]|accessdate=2009-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/pinoy-migration/01/19/09/lockdown-set-obamas-inauguration|title=Lockdown set for Obama's inauguration|date=2006-01-19|publisher=ABS-CBN News ([[Philippines]])|accessdate=2009-05-01}}</ref> [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert Gates]] was chosen as the [[designated survivor]] to ensure [[continuity of government]] in case of catastrophe, and he spent Inauguration Day at a U.S.&nbsp;military installation outside of the Washington,&nbsp;D.C. area.<ref>{{cite news |title=Defense Secretary Will Skip Inauguration |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2009/01/20/defense_secretary_will_skip_in.html?wprss=44 |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |date=2009-01-20 |accessdate=2009-01-21}}</ref>

No one from the crowds at the swearing-in ceremony or parade was arrested on Inauguration Day. According to a senior federal agent associated with managing security, the fact that no arrests were made by any agency during the inaugural events was unheard of for a record crowd of nearly two million gathering in Washington,&nbsp;D.C.<ref name="Washington Post"/><ref>{{cite news |first=James Gordon |last=Meek |title=Security withstands record crowds during President Obama's inauguration parade, swearing-in ceremony |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2009/01/20/2009-01-20_security_withstands_record_crowds_during.html |work=[[The New York Daily News]] |date=2009-01-20 |accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref> In the 2009 book ''[[In the President's Secret Service]]'', author and journalist [[Ronald Kessler]] said intelligence officials received information that individuals associated with [[Al-Shabaab (Somalia)|Al-Shabaab]], a [[Somalia]]-based [[Islamism|Islamist]] insurgency group, might try to disrupt the inauguration. More than a dozen counter-sniper teams were stationed along the inauguration parade route in response, and the criminal records of nearby employees and hotel guests were scrutinized, but no such attack took place. Kessler also reported a number of perceived inadequacies in the security during the inauguration, including an instance in which more than 100 major campaign donors and VIPs were able to board "secure" buses without being checked.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Harnden |first=Toby |title=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2009-08-03 |title=Barack Obama faces 30 death threats a day, stretching US Secret Service |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/barackobama/5967942/Barack-Obama-faces-30-death-threats-a-day-stretching-US-Secret-Service.html |accessdate=2009-08-09}}</ref>

==Viewership==
===Television audience===
[[Nielsen ratings|Nielson television ratings]] indicated that 29.2% of televisions in the 56&nbsp;largest [[United States metropolitan area|media markets]] in the United States were tuned to the inauguration, the largest audience since [[Ronald Reagan]]'s first [[Ronald Reagan 1981 presidential inauguration|inauguration in 1981]] and nearly double the [[viewership]] of the 2005 inauguration of George W. Bush.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,705279305,00.html|title=Obama gets highest TV ratings since Reagan, sets web records|last=Bensinger|first=Greg |date=2009-01-21 |work=[[Deseret News]]|location=[[Salt Lake City, Utah|Salt Lake City,&nbsp;UT]]|accessdate=2009-02-13}}</ref><ref name="neilsen-total">
{{cite-news | last= | first= | title=Obama Inaugural Events Viewed By 29.2% In Top Markets | accessdate= 2009-01-22|date= 2009-01-21| work=Nielsen Wire| url = http://blog.nielsen.com/nielsenwire/media_entertainment/obama-inaugural-events-viewed-by-292-in-top-markets/}}</ref> The Raleigh-Durham market had the largest TV audience with more than 51%&nbsp;of households tuned in to the day's events, a number attributed in part to a snowstorm that kept people inside and in part to the large African American population in that community.<ref name="neilsen-snow">{{cite-news | last= | first= | title=Nielsen: Raleigh-Durham has top ratings for Obama inauguration | accessdate= 2009-01-22|date= 2009-01-21| work=Triangle Business Journal| url = http://www.bizjournals.com/triangle/stories/2009/01/19/daily28.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/01/21/MNRD15EOH7.DTL|title=Nearly 38 million watched inaugural on TV|last=Garofoli|first=Joe |date=January 22, 2009|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle|San&nbsp;Francisco Chronicle]]|accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref> Of the top 10&nbsp;media markets in terms of viewership, four were in North Carolina, two were in Virginia and one was in Maryland, with the Washington D.C. market ranking second highest in television viewership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.nielsen.com/nielsenwire/media_entertainment/obama-inaugural-events-viewed-by-292-in-top-markets/|title=Obama Inaugural Events Viewed By 29.2% In Top Markets|date=2009-0-21|work=Nielson Wire|accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref> In addition, schools and workplaces across the country allowed viewing of the inauguration because the event occurred on a weekday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wdsu.com/news/18514439/detail.html|title=Workplaces Plan For Inauguration Viewing|accessdate=2009-03-28|date=2009-01-19|publisher=[[WDSU|WDSU-TV (New Orleans, LA)]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2009/jan/06/schools-consider-jan-20-tv-time/|title=Schools consider allowing students to watch Obama inauguration|accessdate=2009-03-28|date=2009-01-06|work=[[Memphis Commercial Appeal]]|author=Stout, Cathryn}}</ref> 

As measured between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 5:00&nbsp;p.m.&nbsp;EST, U.S.&nbsp;television viewership for the Obama inaugural events achieved an average of 37.8&nbsp;million across 17&nbsp;broadcast and cable channels, not including [[online]] viewers who watched live streaming video of the events. Although the Obama inaugural events achieved an average U.S.&nbsp;television viewership of 37.8&nbsp;million across both broadcast networks and cable channels, viewership for the events was lower than the U.S.&nbsp;television viewership for the 1981 Reagan inaugural festivities, which averaged 41.8&nbsp;million across the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[CBS]] and [[NBC]] broadcast networks alone.<ref name="viewers">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2009/jan/22/ustelevision-barackobama|title=Barack Obama's inauguration watched by 40m Americans|accessdate=2009-01-23|date=January 22, 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=[[United Kingdom]]|author=Luft, Oliver}}</ref>

Measurements of television viewership in [[Europe]] showed that [[Germany]] drew the largest audience for the Obama inauguration at 11&nbsp;million viewers, followed by [[France]] at 7&nbsp;million viewers and the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland|United Kingdom]] at 5.1&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsmax.com/insidecover/obama_inaugural_reagan/2009/01/22/174132.html?s=al&promo_code=785C-1|title=Obama inaugural ratings fall short of Reagan's|last=Pedraza|first=Rick|date=2009-01-22|publisher=[[Newsmax Media]]|accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvguide.sympatico.msn.ca/Obama+a+huge+TV+success/TVNews/Articles/090122_obama_inauguration_record_MH.htm?isfa=1|title=Obama a huge TV success|last=Hank|first=Melissa|date=2009-01-22|work=[[TV Guide|TV&nbsp;Guide]]|location=[[Canada]]|accessdate=2009-04-17}}</ref> 
According to the [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] (BBC), 6.5&nbsp;million viewers in the United Kingdom watched highlights of the inauguration during its early evening news program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2009/jan/22/tv-ratings-barack-obama-inauguration|title=TV ratings: Barack Obama inauguration draws 5m viewers to BBC1|accessdate=2009-04-13|date=2009-01-22|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=[[United Kingdom]]}}</ref>

===Internet traffic===
The Obama inauguration resulted in a surge of Internet traffic to news and social networking websites and a record number of [[video streams]]. [[CNN]] reported that it generated more than 21&nbsp;million video streams by 3:30&nbsp;p.m.&nbsp;EST that day<U+2014>an all-time record, in addition to receiving 136&nbsp;million [[page view]]s that day.<ref name="internet-traffic" /> At one point during the surge of [[Web traffic|traffic]] to view the Obama inauguration, the BBC reported downtime during its own live video feed at its website. The heavy website traffic caused the BBC video feed to cut out for 30&nbsp;minutes, with web visitors seeing the message "Please come back later" instead of the live video footage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/barackobama/4301367/Barack-Obama-inauguration-record-demand-crashes-BBCs-live-internet-feed.html|title=Barack Obama inauguration: record demand crashes BBC's live internet feed|last=Irvine|first=Chris|date=2009-01-20|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | location=[[United Kingdom]]|accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref> 

The technology company [[Akamai Technologies|Akamai]] reported that 5,401,250&nbsp;web users logged on news sites in less than one minute, the fifth highest peak among news websites since the company started tracking data in 2005.<ref name="internet-traffic">{{cite-news | last=Luft | first=Oliver | title=Web traffic soars for Obama inauguration | accessdate= 2009-01-22|date= 2009-01-23|work=[[The Guardian]]| location=[[United Kingdom]] |url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2009/jan/22/barack-obama-inauguration-web-traffic-soars}}</ref> During at-peak usage, news websites served seven million simultaneous video streams, which was the highest number of simultaneous video streams in Akamai's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/news-sites-struggle-to-stream-obamas-innaguration-speech/|title=News Sites Struggle to Stream Obama Video|accessdate=2009-02-09|date=2009-01-20|work=[[The New York Times|The&nbsp;New York Times]]|author=Vance, Ashlee}}</ref> The Obama inaugural ceremony not only achieved the highest Internet viewership for a U.S.&nbsp;presidential inauguration, the inaugural event was the first to feature a live audio description of a swearing-in ceremony and the first to include [[closed captioning]] in the live [[webcast]] of the event.<ref name="webcast"/>

==International reaction==
{{main|International reaction to the United States presidential election, 2008}}
[[File:Kenyans observing Barack Obama's 2009 Inaugural Address.jpg|235px|thumb|alt=Audience seated in rows, smiling and clapping|Kenyans observing the inauguration from the [[Diplomatic missions of the United States|United States embassy]] in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]]]]
The [[international community]] paid unprecedented attention to the inauguration of Barack Obama. Millions of people, including citizens of numerous countries around the world and American [[expatriate]]s living in those countries, watched the Obama inauguration live on television and on the Internet. In some countries, the Obama inauguration garnered as much viewership as the [[opening ceremony]] of the [[2008 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=kdn>{{cite news |first=|last=|title= History made as Obama sworn in |url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/-/1056/517048/-/u1bo54/-/index.html |work= [[Daily Nation]] |location=[[Kenya]] |date=2009-01-19 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref> 

Celebrations surrounding the inauguration, praise of the event's significance and congratulations to Obama on his inauguration were internationally diverse. In [[Kenya]], the home country of Obama's father, people celebrated the inauguration as a public holiday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7833101.stm|title=TV row over Kenya Obama 'junket' |accessdate=2009-03-13|date=2009-01-16|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref> [[Indonesia]]ns and Americans in [[Jakarta]] watched the inauguration at a free midnight ball featuring performances by students from [[State Elementary School Menteng 01]], the school that Obama attended as a child.<ref name=usa2day>{{cite news |first=Zoe|last=Aslop|title= Kenyans' inaugural trip to USA riles some at home |url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2009-01-19-worldinauguration_N.htm |work= [[USA Today]] |publisher= |date=2009-01-19 |accessdate=2009-01-19}}</ref> The city of [[Obama, Fukui|Obama]] in [[Japan]] celebrated the event with fireworks, bell-ringing and hula-dancing at the Hagaji Temple.<ref name="WSJBlogJapan">{{cite news |first=Miho |last=Inada |title= Early Inauguration Celebration in Obama, Japan  |url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2009/01/20/early-inauguration-celebration-in-obama-japan/ |work= [[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher= |date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2009-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28753038/displaymode/1107/s/2/framenumber/21/|title="Photo:Obama girls" dance the hula to celebrate the inauguration of President Barack Obama|author=Ota, Kiyoshi|date=2009-01-21|accessdate=2009-03-06|publisher=[[MSNBC.com]]}}</ref> [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[Micha<U+00EB>lle Jean]] and [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Stephen Harper]] of [[Canada]] extended congratulations on behalf of Canadians,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?category=3&id=2391|title=Statement by Prime Minister Stephen Harper|accessdate=2009-01-21|date=2009-01-20|publisher=Office of the Prime Minister of Canada}}</ref> while [[President of Mexico|Mexican President]] [[Felipe Calder<U+00F3>n]] wished Obama "great success in the work as the new President of the United States".<ref name=worldcongrats>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/20/obama.international.reaction/index.html|title=World congratulates Obama on taking office|date=2009-01-21|publisher=[[Cable News Network]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> [[Israeli President]] [[Shimon Peres]] described Obama's inauguration as a "great day" for the United States,<ref name=WLACoOI>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,3963354,00.html|title=World Leaders, Adversaries Comment on Obama Inauguration |accessdate=2009-03-21|date=2009-01-20|work=[[Deutsche Welle]]}}</ref> and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] noted that "The whole world is watching the inauguration of President Obama, witnessing a new chapter in both American history and the world's history."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/obama_inauguration/7840565.stm|title=In quotes:Leaders welcome Obama|date=2009-01-20|accessdate=2009-01-21|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>

Leaders of some countries reserved enthusiasm for the Obama inauguration, with coverage of the inauguration even muted in some places. [[President of Cuba|Cuban President]] [[Ra<U+00FA>l Castro]], brother of former Cuban president [[Fidel Castro]], declared that "[Obama] looks like a good man, I hope he is lucky",<ref name=cubacongrats>{{cite news|url=http://www.topnews.in/raul-castro-calls-obama-good-man-wishes-him-luck-2113300|title=Raul Castro calls Obama "a good man", wishes him luck|date=2009-01-21|publisher=''TopNews Magazine'' (India)|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> while [[Ricardo Alarc<U+00F3>n]], president of the [[National Assembly of People's Power|Cuban legislature]], admitted in his comments about Obama that "the incoming [U.S.] president 'is a big question mark.'"<ref name=cubacongrats/> [[Foreign Minister of Iran|Iranian Foreign Minister]] [[Manouchehr Mottaki]] expressed hope for openness for a new direction, noting that "if Obama chooses the right path, compensates the past, lifts hostility and U.S.&nbsp;hegemony, and revises the previous political mistakes, we will have no hostility."<ref name="WLACoOI"/> State-owned [[Channel One Russia]], [[Russia]]'s flagship early evening news show, covered Obama's presidential inauguration as a minor news story, devoting much of the day's airtime instead to the gas war with Ukraine.<ref name=WwOi>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117998807.html?categoryid=1064&cs=1|title=World watches Obama inauguration: International audiences have mixed views|accessdate=2009-03-11|date=2009-01-20|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Thomas, Archie}}</ref> The [[People's Republic of China]] covered the Obama inauguration live on its state<U+2011>controlled [[China Central Television]], providing simultaneous translation into [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin Chinese]] with a brief delay to allow [[Censorship in the People's Republic of China|censoring]] of Obama's comments. When President Obama mentioned "earlier generations faced down [[fascism]] and [[communism]]", Chinese state television officials cut away abruptly from the televised speech and switched to a discussion in the studio.<ref name="bbcbristow">{{cite web|last=Bristow|first=Michael|title=Obama speech censored in China|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=2009-01-21|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/asia-pacific/7841580.stm|accessdate=2009-01-21}}</ref><ref name="scranton">{{cite web | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | accessdate=2009-03-02 | last=Chang | first=Anita | date=2009-01-21 | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/21/china-censors-parts-of-ob_n_159603.html| title=China Censors Parts Of Obama's Speech}}</ref> State-controlled print, radio and television media in [[North Korea]] provided no coverage or mention of the Obama inauguration in the hours after the event, opting instead to cover news about [[Equatorial Guinea]] welcoming the North Korean ambassador.<ref name=bbcworld>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/obama_inauguration/7839486.stm|title=World hopes on Obama|date=2009-01-21|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> 

Ordinary citizens in [[Iraq]] even offered comments about the new president with cautious optimism. One Iraqi citizen opined that "If [Obama] can do as well as he talks, then all our problems are over", adding a belief that "[Obama] is a good man, but many people in Iraq believe all American presidents are the same and that we are a playground for their interests."<ref name=iraqview>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/jan/20/obama-inauguration-global-reaction|title=Jubilation and resignation as world reacts to arrival of new US president|last=Dehghan|first=Saeed Kamali|coauthors=Rice, Xan; Harding, Luke; Chulov, Martin; Carroll, Rory  and McCarthy, Rory |date=2009-01-21|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=[[United Kingdom]]|accessdate=2009-04-27}}</ref> Another citizen noted that "Obama won't get the same treatment,'&nbsp;... 'But he won't have too long to prove himself to us.'"<ref name=iraqview/>

